{"title_page": "Kenan G\u00f6rg\u00fcn", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Kenan Gorgun\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1977|04|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n|occupation  = [[film director]], [[scriptwriter]], writer\n|nationality = Belgian\n}}\n'''Kenan G\u00f6rg\u00fcn''' (born 18 April 1977) is a Belgian writer of Turkish origin, born in [[Ghent]].\n\nHe has been studying in a French-speaking school in [[Brussels]].<br />\nHe studied writing with his professor Gustave Rongy and wrote his first poems and short stories for a magazine called \"Marginales\".<ref>[http://marginales.free.fr/ Marginales]</ref><br />\nAs a scriptwriter, he has been honored with prizes and is a member of the Association des Sc\u00e9naristes de l'Audiovisuel.<ref>[http://www.associationscenaristes.be/ ASA]</ref><br />\nHe wrote songs for the rock band O.I.L.<ref>[http://www.oilmusic.be Orange Indelible Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040104105936/http://www.oilmusic.be/ |date=January 4, 2004 }}</ref><br />\nHis latest novel, Patriot Act, features a cop named Elvis Casanova. He has already scheduled 5 more of his adventures...<br />\nIn 2011, he shot his first feature-length film, called Yadel, produced by Saga Film Belgium.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* 2005: \"L'Enfer est \u00e0 nous\", Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium, Quadrature<ref>[http://www.editionsquadrature.be/ \u00c9ditions Quadrature]</ref>\n* 2006: \"M\u00e9moires d'un cendrier sale\" \u2013 Bookleg N\u00b010, Brussels, Belgium, Maelstrom<ref>[http://www.maelstromeditions.com \u00c9ditions Maelstrom]</ref>\n* 2006: \"L'ogre, c'est mon enfant\", Avin, Belgium, \u00c9ditions Luce Wilquin\n* 2007: \"Fosse commune\", Paris, France, Fayard\n* 2008: \"Alcool de larmes\" Brussels, Belgium, \u00c9ditions Luce Wilquin\n* 2009: \"Patriot Act\", Paris, France, First Editions<ref>[http://www.efirst.com First Editions]</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 2008: \"9mm\", a movie by Taylan Barman, scriptwriter\n* 2011: \"Yadel\", scriptwriter and director, produced by Saga Film\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{IMDb name|2410056}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorgun, Kenan}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Ghent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Kenan Gorgun\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1977|04|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n|occupation  = [[film director]], [[scriptwriter]], writer\n|nationality = Belgian\n}}\n'''Kenan G\u00f6rg\u00fcn''' (born 18 April 1977) is a Belgian writer of Turkish origin, born in [[Ghent]].\n\nHe has been studying in a French-speaking school in [[Brussels]].<br />\nHe studied writing with his professor Gustave Rongy and wrote his first poems and short stories for a magazine called \"Marginales\".<ref>[http://marginales.free.fr/ Marginales]</ref><br />\nAs a scriptwriter, he has been honored with prizes and is a member of the Association des Sc\u00e9naristes de l'Audiovisuel.<ref>[http://www.associationscenaristes.be/ ASA]</ref><br />\nHe wrote songs for the rock band O.I.L.<ref>[http://www.oilmusic.be Orange Indelible Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040104105936/http://www.oilmusic.be/ |date=January 4, 2004 }}</ref><br />\nHis latest novel, Patriot Act, features a cop named Elvis Casanova. He has already scheduled 5 more of his adventures...<br />\nIn 2011, he shot his first feature-length film, called Yadel, produced by Saga Film Belgium.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* 2005: \"L'Enfer est \u00e0 nous\", Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium, Quadrature<ref>[http://www.editionsquadrature.be/ \u00c9ditions Quadrature]</ref>\n* 2006: \"M\u00e9moires d'un cendrier sale\" \u2013 Bookleg N\u00b010, Brussels, Belgium, Maelstrom<ref>[http://www.maelstromeditions.com \u00c9ditions Maelstrom]</ref>\n* 2006: \"L'ogre, c'est mon enfant\", Avin, Belgium, \u00c9ditions Luce Wilquin\n* 2007: \"Fosse commune\", Paris, France, Fayard\n* 2008: \"Alcool de larmes\" Brussels, Belgium, \u00c9ditions Luce Wilquin\n* 2009: \"Patriot Act\", Paris, France, First Editions<ref>[http://www.efirst.com First Editions]</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 2008: \"9mm\", a movie by Taylan Barman, scriptwriter\n* 2011: \"Yadel\", scriptwriter and director, produced by Saga Film\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{IMDb name|2410056}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorgun, Kenan}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Ghent]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenan_G%C3%B6rg%C3%BCn"}
{"title_page": "Julien Friedler", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Julien Friedler\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = 280px\n| caption       =\n| birth_name     = Julien Friedler\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|11|13}}\n| birth_place    = [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n| field         = [[Literature]], [[painting]], [[sculpture]], [[drawing]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = [[Be art]]\n| works         = The Demoiselles revisited,<ref>Galerie Francis Naumann, New York, 2007</ref> In Quest<ref>Galerie Philippe Seghers, Ostende, 2007</ref>\n| influenced_by =\n| influenced    =\n}}\n'''Julien Friedler''' (born 1950), a writer and [[contemporary art]]ist, is the leading figure in the visual art movement known as Be art.  Friedler was born in 1950 in [[Brussels]].\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nFriedler spent his childhood and adolescence in Brussels. He earned university degrees in [[philosophy]] at La Sorbonne and [[ethnography]] at the Universit\u00e9 Libre of Brussels. He then studied [[psychoanalysis]] in Paris, following the [[post-structuralist]] theories of [[Jacques Lacan]], while starting a personal psychoanalysis with Lacan. He had wide-ranging interests and subsequently trained in [[jewellery]] design. In the 1990s he established \"La Moire\"<ref>[http://cahiersdelamoire.blogspot.com/ Website of \u00ab La Moire \u00bb, the psychoanalysis school created by Julien Friedler] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708030243/http://cahiersdelamoire.blogspot.com/ |date= 8 July 2011 }}</ref> in Brussels, an institute to promote an interdisciplinary approach within the psychoanalytic field. He aimed to break through the constraints of classical psychoanalysis but encountered considerable resistance and ultimately left the psychoanalytical milieu.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\nFriedler began his artistic career in 1994. He was entirely self-taught but his insight into the human character and a fascination for the unknown led him to start painting. Through his art, he confronted [[postmodern]] contemporary society and the events of the second half of the 20th century. He emerged as a charismatic visionary taking a [[holistic]] approach while creating an organic [[Macrocosm and microcosm|microcosm]], the ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20101213025056/http://www.spiritofboz.org/ World of Boz]''.\n\n== Literature ==\nDuring his career, Friedler wrote numerous articles and books which earned critical acclaim in the psychoanalytic field.<ref>Psychoanalyse et neurosciences: La L\u00e9gende du Boiteux (PUF, 1995), L'Oeil d'Oedipe (PUF, 2004), poetical essays and fictions</ref> In 2003 he set out to write an epic literary work entitled ''The Book of Boz''. The Book of Boz is simultaneously a novel and a work of poetry, written mostly as a dialogue. The story unfolds in the 20th century, in the present, and in a fictitious future. The main characters are three clowns: Jack Balance, Friedler himself, and the Mirror Man.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\n== Visual work ==\nSome of Friedler's paintings are done in a [[neo-expressionist]] style. Others feature shamanic stick figures that glow with inner energy or are lined with quasi-primitive symbols resembling Egyptian [[hieroglyphs]]; in particular, \"The Word of Angels\" depicts Friedler's self-conceived language whereby the artist refers to primeval myths that honor the connection between the supernatural and the profane as a theme.<ref>La Parole des Anges, Cazeau B\u00e9reaudi\u00e8re Gallery, Paris, 2005</ref> The youthful language of [[graffiti]] also appears in some works.<ref>BeBoz I, Michael Darling, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\nMuch of Friedler's work contains biographical references, but these are often ambiguous. In order to understand Friedler's work it is necessary to understand some of the significant events in the artist's history and life, such as the [[Shoah]] and [[May 1968]]. The artist's visual work takes a central place in ''The Book of Boz'' and in the book he is forced to ultimately present his art to a wider audience and simultaneously confront the contemporary international art scene.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\n== Association ==\nIn 2008 Friedler created a contemporary art association called Spirit of Boz,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spiritofboz.org/ |title=Spirit Of Boz, Julien Friedler's works as hypertext |access-date=28 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213025056/http://www.spiritofboz.org/ |archive-date=13 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which coordinates the [[Be Boz Be Art]] programme.<ref>[http://www.beboz.org/ Be Boz Be Art programme, news and informations]</ref> This programme involves cultural and artistic projects conceived explicitly as art \"for and by the masses\". Friedler operates within his association, rather than be part of the art scene, and in doing so aims to make art accessible for a wide audience and in areas where art is least expected or entirely out of place. In that context art is used as a vehicle for improving social cohesion.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Mosa\u00efque'' (1982) {{ISBN|2-86705-006-5}}\n* ''L'ombre du rabbin'' (1985) {{ISBN|2-86705-043-X}}\n* ''Psychanalyse et neurosciences : La L\u00e9gende du Boiteux'' (1995) {{ISBN|2-13-046909-4}}\n* ''L'ivrogne'' (1998) {{ISBN|2-912668-04-2}}\n* ''Tiresias'' (1998) {{ISBN|2-85446-246-7}}\n* ''L'\u0153il d'\u0152dipe'' (2004) {{ISBN|2-13-054060-0}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110227042049/http://rebelle.blogspirit.com/julien_friedler/ Photos taken by Sonia Bressler in the Brussels artist's studio]\n*[http://perso.orange.fr/maurice.villard/noteslec.htm#neurosc Reading notes in French on \u00ab Psychoanalysis and neuroscience \u00bb written by Julien Friedler]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friedler, Julien}}\n[[Category:Contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Brussels]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Julien Friedler\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = 280px\n| caption       =\n| birth_name     = Julien Friedler\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|11|13}}\n| birth_place    = [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n| field         = [[Literature]], [[painting]], [[sculpture]], [[drawing]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = [[Be art]]\n| works         = The Demoiselles revisited,<ref>Galerie Francis Naumann, New York, 2007</ref> In Quest<ref>Galerie Philippe Seghers, Ostende, 2007</ref>\n| influenced_by =\n| influenced    =\n}}\n'''Julien Friedler''' (born 1950), a writer and [[contemporary art]]ist, is the leading figure in the visual art movement known as Be art.  Friedler was born in 1950 in [[Brussels]].\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nFriedler spent his childhood and adolescence in Brussels. He earned university degrees in [[philosophy]] at La Sorbonne and [[ethnography]] at the Universit\u00e9 Libre of Brussels. He then studied [[psychoanalysis]] in Paris, following the [[post-structuralist]] theories of [[Jacques Lacan]], while starting a personal psychoanalysis with Lacan. He had wide-ranging interests and subsequently trained in [[jewellery]] design. In the 1990s he established \"La Moire\"<ref>[http://cahiersdelamoire.blogspot.com/ Website of \u00ab La Moire \u00bb, the psychoanalysis school created by Julien Friedler] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708030243/http://cahiersdelamoire.blogspot.com/ |date= 8 July 2011 }}</ref> in Brussels, an institute to promote an interdisciplinary approach within the psychoanalytic field. He aimed to break through the constraints of classical psychoanalysis but encountered considerable resistance and ultimately left the psychoanalytical milieu.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\nFriedler began his artistic career in 1994. He was entirely self-taught but his insight into the human character and a fascination for the unknown led him to start painting. Through his art, he confronted [[postmodern]] contemporary society and the events of the second half of the 20th century. He emerged as a charismatic visionary taking a [[holistic]] approach while creating an organic [[Macrocosm and microcosm|microcosm]], the ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20101213025056/http://www.spiritofboz.org/ World of Boz]''.\n\n== Literature ==\nDuring his career, Friedler wrote numerous articles and books which earned critical acclaim in the psychoanalytic field.<ref>Psychoanalyse et neurosciences: La L\u00e9gende du Boiteux (PUF, 1995), L'Oeil d'Oedipe (PUF, 2004), poetical essays and fictions</ref> In 2003 he set out to write an epic literary work entitled ''The Book of Boz''. The Book of Boz is simultaneously a novel and a work of poetry, written mostly as a dialogue. The story unfolds in the 20th century, in the present, and in a fictitious future. The main characters are three clowns: Jack Balance, Friedler himself, and the Mirror Man.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\n== Visual work ==\nSome of Friedler's paintings are done in a [[neo-expressionist]] style. Others feature shamanic stick figures that glow with inner energy or are lined with quasi-primitive symbols resembling Egyptian [[hieroglyphs]]; in particular, \"The Word of Angels\" depicts Friedler's self-conceived language whereby the artist refers to primeval myths that honor the connection between the supernatural and the profane as a theme.<ref>La Parole des Anges, Cazeau B\u00e9reaudi\u00e8re Gallery, Paris, 2005</ref> The youthful language of [[graffiti]] also appears in some works.<ref>BeBoz I, Michael Darling, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\nMuch of Friedler's work contains biographical references, but these are often ambiguous. In order to understand Friedler's work it is necessary to understand some of the significant events in the artist's history and life, such as the [[Shoah]] and [[May 1968]]. The artist's visual work takes a central place in ''The Book of Boz'' and in the book he is forced to ultimately present his art to a wider audience and simultaneously confront the contemporary international art scene.<ref>BeBoz III, Erno Vroonen, Editions du Chaman, 2009</ref>\n\n== Association ==\nIn 2008 Friedler created a contemporary art association called Spirit of Boz,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spiritofboz.org/ |title=Spirit Of Boz, Julien Friedler's works as hypertext |access-date=28 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213025056/http://www.spiritofboz.org/ |archive-date=13 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which coordinates the [[Be Boz Be Art]] programme.<ref>[http://www.beboz.org/ Be Boz Be Art programme, news and informations]</ref> This programme involves cultural and artistic projects conceived explicitly as art \"for and by the masses\". Friedler operates within his association, rather than be part of the art scene, and in doing so aims to make art accessible for a wide audience and in areas where art is least expected or entirely out of place. In that context art is used as a vehicle for improving social cohesion.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Mosa\u00efque'' (1982) {{ISBN|2-86705-006-5}}\n* ''L'ombre du rabbin'' (1985) {{ISBN|2-86705-043-X}}\n* ''Psychanalyse et neurosciences : La L\u00e9gende du Boiteux'' (1995) {{ISBN|2-13-046909-4}}\n* ''L'ivrogne'' (1998) {{ISBN|2-912668-04-2}}\n* ''Tiresias'' (1998) {{ISBN|2-85446-246-7}}\n* ''L'\u0153il d'\u0152dipe'' (2004) {{ISBN|2-13-054060-0}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110227042049/http://rebelle.blogspirit.com/julien_friedler/ Photos taken by Sonia Bressler in the Brussels artist's studio]\n*[http://perso.orange.fr/maurice.villard/noteslec.htm#neurosc Reading notes in French on \u00ab Psychoanalysis and neuroscience \u00bb written by Julien Friedler]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friedler, Julien}}\n[[Category:Contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:People from Brussels]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julien_Friedler"}
{"title_page": "Valery Votrin", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n|name = Val\u00e9ry Votrin\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|03|02}}\n|birth_place =  [[Tashkent]], [[USSR]]\n|nationality = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n||death_date =\n|death_place =\n|occupation = Writer, translator, environmental consultant\n| genre         = [[magic realism]], [[weird fiction]] }}\n\n'''Val\u00e9ry Votrin''' ([[Russian people|Russian]]: \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u0301\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043d, born March 2, 1974) is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] fiction writer of [[Russian language|Russian]] origin. He writes in Russian and English (under the name Val Votrin).\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Tashkent]], [[Soviet Union]] into a Russian family, he studied English Language and Literature at the Faculty of Germanic and Romance Studies at [[National University of Uzbekistan|Tashkent State University]]. In 2000, he moved to Belgium where he received an [[Master of Science|MSc]] degree in [[Human Ecology]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree in [[Environmental Science]] from the [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel|Free University of Brussels (VUB)]]. He has worked as an environmental consultant specialising in environmental [[due diligence]] and [[environmental audit|auditing]].\n\nHe has published short stories and novels since 1995. In 2009, his novel The Last Magog was shortlisted for the [[Andrei Bely Prize]], the oldest independent literary prize in Russia. Another novel, The Speech Therapist was nominated for a string of literary awards, including the [[Russian Booker Prize]], the Big Book Prize and the [[Alexander Piatigorsky]] Prize.\n\nHe translated and published short stories by [[Flann O\u2019Brien]], [[T. F. Powys]], and [[Eric Stenbock]] as well as numerous poems by the 17th \u2013 20th century English and Scottish poets, including [[Francis Quarles]], [[Jeremy Taylor]], [[Phineas Fletcher]], [[Robert Southey]], [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]], [[A. E. Housman]], [[William Soutar]], and [[Robert Garioch]]. His poetry translations are mainly collected in an anthology \u201cSeven Centuries of English Poetry\u201d (Moscow, Vodolei Publishers, 2007). In 2012, he published his translation of [[The City of Dreadful Night]], a long poem by [[James Thomson (B.V.)|James Thomson]].\n\nVotrin also collected a two-volume Russian edition of plays and short stories by Belgian dramatist [[Michel De Ghelderode]] in 2004.\n\n== Published books ==\n* ''The Book of Prayers and Complaints'' (\u0416\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432, 2007)\n* ''The Last Magog'' (\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0433, 2008)\n* ''The Speech Therapist'' (\u041b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434, 2012)\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n* {{in lang|ru}} [[Alexei Parshchikov]], [http://magazines.russ.ru/nlo/2008/92/par24.html ''Leaving Arcadia''], a review in the ''New Literary Observer'', 2008.\n* {{in lang|ru}} [[Alexander Chantsev]], [http://magazines.russ.ru/nlo/2008/92/cha26.html ''The Swathed History''], a review in the ''New Literary Observer'', 2008.\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://www.litkarta.ru/world/belgium/persons/votrin-v Val\u00e9ry Votrin] at the ''New Literary Map of Russia''\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://magazines.russ.ru/authors/v/votrin/ A collection of Val\u00e9ry Votrin\u2019s texts] in literary magazines\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Votrin, Valery}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tashkent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:National University of Uzbekistan alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n|name = Val\u00e9ry Votrin\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|03|02}}\n|birth_place =  [[Tashkent]], [[USSR]]\n|nationality = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n||death_date =\n|death_place =\n|occupation = Writer, translator, environmental consultant\n| genre         = [[magic realism]], [[weird fiction]] }}\n\n'''Val\u00e9ry Votrin''' ([[Russian people|Russian]]: \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0301\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u0301\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043d, born March 2, 1974) is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] fiction writer of [[Russian language|Russian]] origin. He writes in Russian and English (under the name Val Votrin).\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Tashkent]], [[Soviet Union]] into a Russian family, he studied English Language and Literature at the Faculty of Germanic and Romance Studies at [[National University of Uzbekistan|Tashkent State University]]. In 2000, he moved to Belgium where he received an [[Master of Science|MSc]] degree in [[Human Ecology]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree in [[Environmental Science]] from the [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel|Free University of Brussels (VUB)]]. He has worked as an environmental consultant specialising in environmental [[due diligence]] and [[environmental audit|auditing]].\n\nHe has published short stories and novels since 1995. In 2009, his novel The Last Magog was shortlisted for the [[Andrei Bely Prize]], the oldest independent literary prize in Russia. Another novel, The Speech Therapist was nominated for a string of literary awards, including the [[Russian Booker Prize]], the Big Book Prize and the [[Alexander Piatigorsky]] Prize.\n\nHe translated and published short stories by [[Flann O\u2019Brien]], [[T. F. Powys]], and [[Eric Stenbock]] as well as numerous poems by the 17th \u2013 20th century English and Scottish poets, including [[Francis Quarles]], [[Jeremy Taylor]], [[Phineas Fletcher]], [[Robert Southey]], [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]], [[A. E. Housman]], [[William Soutar]], and [[Robert Garioch]]. His poetry translations are mainly collected in an anthology \u201cSeven Centuries of English Poetry\u201d (Moscow, Vodolei Publishers, 2007). In 2012, he published his translation of [[The City of Dreadful Night]], a long poem by [[James Thomson (B.V.)|James Thomson]].\n\nVotrin also collected a two-volume Russian edition of plays and short stories by Belgian dramatist [[Michel De Ghelderode]] in 2004.\n\n== Published books ==\n* ''The Book of Prayers and Complaints'' (\u0416\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432, 2007)\n* ''The Last Magog'' (\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0433, 2008)\n* ''The Speech Therapist'' (\u041b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434, 2012)\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n* {{in lang|ru}} [[Alexei Parshchikov]], [http://magazines.russ.ru/nlo/2008/92/par24.html ''Leaving Arcadia''], a review in the ''New Literary Observer'', 2008.\n* {{in lang|ru}} [[Alexander Chantsev]], [http://magazines.russ.ru/nlo/2008/92/cha26.html ''The Swathed History''], a review in the ''New Literary Observer'', 2008.\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://www.litkarta.ru/world/belgium/persons/votrin-v Val\u00e9ry Votrin] at the ''New Literary Map of Russia''\n* {{in lang|ru}} [http://magazines.russ.ru/authors/v/votrin/ A collection of Val\u00e9ry Votrin\u2019s texts] in literary magazines\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Votrin, Valery}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tashkent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Belgian short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:National University of Uzbekistan alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valery_Votrin"}
{"title_page": "Peter Verhelst", "text_new": "{{short description|Flemish writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Verhelst\n| image       = Peter verhelst-1510668632.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Peter Verhelst in 2017 (Photo by Filip Naudts)\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|1|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Bruges]], Belgium\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgium\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = dramatist, novelist, poet\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Peter Verhelst''' (born 28 January 1962) is a Belgian [[Flemish people|Flemish]] novelist, poet and dramatist. He won the  [[Ferdinand Bordewijk Prijs]] for ''[[Tongkat]]''. His latest novel is a political thriller, ''Zwerm''.\n\n== Life ==\nPeter Verhelst was born in [[Bruges]], Belgium. In his youth, he was extremely interested in books, reading atlases and encyclopaediae, as well as novels, and writing poetry from the age of 16.\n\nWhile a teacher in Dutch, English and History, he debuted in 1987 with the poem \"Obsidiaan\", with his first novel - \"Vloeibaar harnas\" - following in 1993. Thereafter, he worked as a teacher at the Institute for Food in Bruges, quitting in 1999 to begin writing full-time. In 2000, he won the prestigious Gouden Uil ([[Golden Owl]]) and Young Gold Owl (Jonge Gouden Uil), a literary prize for Belgian literature in the Dutch language. He also started working as a playwright, with his first play completed in 1997.\n\nIn 2016 he won the [[Ida Gerhardt Po\u00ebzieprijs]].\n\nVerhelst currently lives and works in [[Bruges, Belgium]].\n\n== Important works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n*''Obsidiaan'' (1987)\n*''OTTO'' (1998)\n*''Angel'' (1990)\n*''Witte Bloemen'' (1991)\n*''Master'' (1992)\n*''De Boom N'' (1994)\n*''Verhemelte'' (1996)\n*''Verrukkingen'' (1997)\n*''Alaska'' (2003)\n*''Nieuwe sterrenbeelden'' (2008)\n*''Zoo van het denken'' (2011)\n\n=== Prose ===\n*''Vloeibaar harnas'' (1993)\n*''Het spieren alfabet'' (1995)\n*''De kleurenvanger'' (1996)\n*''[[Tongkat]]'' (1999)\n*''Zwellend fruit'' (2000)\n*''Memoires van een Luipaard'' (2001)\n*''Mondschilderingen'' (2002)\n*''Zwerm'' (2005)\n*''Huis van de Aanrakingen'' (2010)\n*''De allerlaatste caracara ter wereld'' (2012)\n*''[[The Man I Became|Geschiedenis van een berg]]'' (2013)\n*''De kunst van het crashen'' (2015)\n*''De zeer vermoeide man en de vrouw die hartstochtelijk van bonsai hield'' (2016)\n*''Voor het vergeten'' (2018)\n\n=== Theater ===\n*''Maria Salom\u00e9'' (1997)\n*''Romeo en Julia (studie van een verdrinkend lichaam)'' (1998)\n*''Red Rubber Balls'' (1999)\n*''S*ckmyp'' (2000)\n*''AARS!'' (2000)\n*''Scratching the inner fields'' (2001)\n*''Philocrates'' (2002)\n*''Het sprookjesbordeel'' (2002)\n*''Blush' (2002)\n*''Sonic Boom'' (2002)\n*''Icarus/Man-o-War'' (2002) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Philoctetes Fortify My Arms'' (2003) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Crash'' (2004) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Terra Nova'' (2011) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Absence'' (October 2015) [[CREW Eric Joris]] and NTGent\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Flemish literature]]\n* [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425092112/http://home.medewerker.uva.nl/t.l.vaessens/bestanden/Vaessens%20Verhelst.pdf Over Verhelsts po\u00ebzie ([[Dutch language|Dutch]])]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051028112852/http://www.neerlandistiek.nl/01.10/ Over Verhelsts Tongkat (Dutch)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verhelst, Peter}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bruges]]\n[[Category:Flemish poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Ferdinand Bordewijk Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:Male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian speculative fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:Woutertje Pieterse Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Gouden Griffel winners]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Flemish writer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Verhelst\n| image       = Peter verhelst-1510668632.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Peter Verhelst in 2017 (Photo by Filip Naudts)\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|1|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Bruges]], Belgium\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgium\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = dramatist, novelist, poet\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Peter Verhelst''' (born 28 January 1962) is a Belgian [[Flemish people|Flemish]] novelist, poet and dramatist. He won the  [[Ferdinand Bordewijk Prijs]] for ''[[Tongkat]]''. His latest novel is a political thriller, ''Zwerm''.\n\n== Life ==\nPeter Verhelst was born in [[Bruges]], Belgium. In his youth, he was extremely interested in books, reading atlases and encyclopaediae, as well as novels, and writing poetry from the age of 16.\n\nWhile a teacher in Dutch, English and History, he debuted in 1987 with the poem \"Obsidiaan\", with his first novel - \"Vloeibaar harnas\" - following in 1993. Thereafter, he worked as a teacher at the Institute for Food in Bruges, quitting in 1999 to begin writing full-time. In 2000, he won the prestigious Gouden Uil ([[Golden Owl]]) and Young Gold Owl (Jonge Gouden Uil), a literary prize for Belgian literature in the Dutch language. He also started working as a playwright, with his first play completed in 1997.\n\nIn 2016 he won the [[Ida Gerhardt Po\u00ebzieprijs]].\n\nVerhelst currently lives and works in [[Bruges, Belgium]].\n\n== Important works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n*''Obsidiaan'' (1987)\n*''OTTO'' (1998)\n*''Angel'' (1990)\n*''Witte Bloemen'' (1991)\n*''Master'' (1992)\n*''De Boom N'' (1994)\n*''Verhemelte'' (1996)\n*''Verrukkingen'' (1997)\n*''Alaska'' (2003)\n*''Nieuwe sterrenbeelden'' (2008)\n*''Zoo van het denken'' (2011)\n\n=== Prose ===\n*''Vloeibaar harnas'' (1993)\n*''Het spieren alfabet'' (1995)\n*''De kleurenvanger'' (1996)\n*''[[Tongkat]]'' (1999)\n*''Zwellend fruit'' (2000)\n*''Memoires van een Luipaard'' (2001)\n*''Mondschilderingen'' (2002)\n*''Zwerm'' (2005)\n*''Huis van de Aanrakingen'' (2010)\n*''De allerlaatste caracara ter wereld'' (2012)\n*''[[The Man I Became|Geschiedenis van een berg]]'' (2013)\n*''De kunst van het crashen'' (2015)\n*''De zeer vermoeide man en de vrouw die hartstochtelijk van bonsai hield'' (2016)\n*''Voor het vergeten'' (2018)\n\n=== Theater ===\n*''Maria Salom\u00e9'' (1997)\n*''Romeo en Julia (studie van een verdrinkend lichaam)'' (1998)\n*''Red Rubber Balls'' (1999)\n*''S*ckmyp'' (2000)\n*''AARS!'' (2000)\n*''Scratching the inner fields'' (2001)\n*''Philocrates'' (2002)\n*''Het sprookjesbordeel'' (2002)\n*''Blush' (2002)\n*''Sonic Boom'' (2002)\n*''Icarus/Man-o-War'' (2002) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Philoctetes Fortify My Arms'' (2003) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Crash'' (2004) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Terra Nova'' (2011) [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n*''Absence'' (October 2015) [[CREW Eric Joris]] and NTGent\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Flemish literature]]\n* [[CREW Eric Joris]]\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120425092112/http://home.medewerker.uva.nl/t.l.vaessens/bestanden/Vaessens%20Verhelst.pdf Over Verhelsts po\u00ebzie ([[Dutch language|Dutch]])]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051028112852/http://www.neerlandistiek.nl/01.10/ Over Verhelsts Tongkat (Dutch)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verhelst, Peter}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bruges]]\n[[Category:Flemish poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Ferdinand Bordewijk Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:Male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian speculative fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Woutertje Pieterse Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Gouden Griffel winners]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Verhelst"}
{"title_page": "Paul Verhaeghen", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian novelist}}\n'''Paul Verhaeghen''' (born 1965) is a Belgian novelist, writing in his native [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. His novels include ''Lichtenberg''<ref>{{cite book|title=Lichtenberg: Een roman, hoewel opgebouwd uit slechts twee vragen, toch verdeeld in dertien hoofdstukken (Dutch Edition): Paul Verhaeghen: 9789022313992: Amazon.com: Books |date=1996-01-01 |isbn = 9022313999}}</ref> (1996) and ''[[Omega Minor]]'' (2004). ''Omega Minor'' has been translated into [[German language|German]] (2006, Eichborn Verlag), English (2007, [[Dalkey Archive Press]]) French (2010, Le Cherche midi / Lot 49), and Hungarian (2011, Gondolat Kiad\u00f3). The Dutch version won the [[Ferdinand Bordewijk Prijs]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jancampertstichting.nl/prijzen/archief_prijswinnaars.htm |accessdate=8 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208154748/http://www.jancampertstichting.nl/prijzen/archief_prijswinnaars.htm |archivedate=8 December 2004 }}</ref> and the Culture Award of the Flemish Government (2006), as well as the Award for Prose of the Joint Flemish Provinces (2007).<ref>[http://www.vlaamsbrabant.be/vrije-tijd-cultuur/cultuur/literatuur/literatuurprijs/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608071448/http://www.vlaamsbrabant.be/vrije-tijd-cultuur/cultuur/literatuur/literatuurprijs/ |date=8 June 2011 }}</ref> The English translation, done by the author himself, won the 2008 [[Independent Foreign Fiction Prize]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Boyd |last=Tonkin |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/independent-foreign-fiction-prize-goodbye-to-berlin-823357.html|publisher=Independent.co.uk |title=Independent Foreign Fiction Prize: Goodbye to Berlin |date=9 May 2008 |accessdate= 7 November 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20080521213132/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/pressnews/press_detail.php?rid=10&id=1136]</ref>\n\nVerhaeghen is also a [[Cognitive psychology|cognitive psychologist]], currently working at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. He studied theoretical psychology at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven|Catholic University of Leuven]] (Katholieke Universiteit Leuven) in Belgium. In 1993 he earned his Dr.Psyc. degree with the thesis ''Teaching old dogs new memory tricks: Plasticity in episodic memory performance in old age''.<ref>DAI-C 55/03, p. 1018, Fall 1994</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verhaeghen, Paul}}\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Ferdinand Bordewijk Prize winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian novelist}}\n'''Paul Verhaeghen''' (born 1965) is a Belgian novelist, writing in his native [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. His novels include ''Lichtenberg''<ref>{{cite book|title=Lichtenberg: Een roman, hoewel opgebouwd uit slechts twee vragen, toch verdeeld in dertien hoofdstukken (Dutch Edition): Paul Verhaeghen: 9789022313992: Amazon.com: Books |date=1996-01-01 |isbn = 9022313999}}</ref> (1996) and ''[[Omega Minor]]'' (2004). ''Omega Minor'' has been translated into [[German language|German]] (2006, Eichborn Verlag), English (2007, [[Dalkey Archive Press]]) French (2010, Le Cherche midi / Lot 49), and Hungarian (2011, Gondolat Kiad\u00f3). The Dutch version won the [[Ferdinand Bordewijk Prijs]] in 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jancampertstichting.nl/prijzen/archief_prijswinnaars.htm |accessdate=8 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208154748/http://www.jancampertstichting.nl/prijzen/archief_pri