{"title_page": "Jan Vanriet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Jan Vanriet\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = Photo of the artist\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age |df=yes|1948|2|21|}}\n| birth_place   = [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]]\n| nationality = Belgian\n| field         = Painting, Poetry\n| training      = [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Antwerp]]\n}}\n\n'''Jan Vanriet''', real name Jan Louis Lucien Vanriet, (21 February 1948) is a [[Belgian]] ([[Flemish]]) painter and poet.<ref name=\"webhosting1\">http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/biography/</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet.jpg|thumb|left|x220px]]\nJan Vanriet was born in Antwerp and attended the Royal Atheneum of Hoboken where the art critic and promotor [[:nl:Marcel van Jole|Marcel van Jole]] was one of his teachers.<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/category/blog/</ref>  In 1965, while visiting Prague, he met the avant-garde graphic artist [[:de:Pravoslav Sovak|Pravoslav Sovak]], who at 22 years older, became his mentor.  The following year Vanriet was invited to the artist's studio in South Bohemia, where he painted a series of landscapes. Their friendship continues today.\n\nIn 1968, Vanriet started painting studies at the [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Fine Arts in Antwerp]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">''Jan Vanriet: It may be that people are able to learn lessons from the past'', Darya Palatkina, The Art Newspaper, Russia</ref>   As a young art student and a debuting poet, he became deeply involved in writers' actions against literary censorship in Belgium, actions that became very famous when he organised a Protest Read-In at the Majestic Theatre in Antwerp, with 40 authors on stage and an audience of over 1000. A second Read-In was organised at [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Palais des Beaux-Arts in Brussels]] (Bozar). It was here that he met his future wife, Simone Lenaerts.<ref>''Jarig in mijn schitterend woord: opstellen over Hugues C. Pernath'', Academia Press, 2012, {{ISBN|978 90 382 2029 1}}, p.69</ref>\n\nIn 1971, he became the youngest member of the editing council of the influential political monthly ''De Nieuwe Maand'' (''The New Month''), a group of ambitious politicians from catholic and socialist parties, amongst them, the later prime ministers [[Jean-Luc Dehaene]] and [[Wilfried Martens]], and European Commissar [[Karel van Miert]].<ref>''Tussen bescherming en verovering: sociologen en historici over zuilvorming'', ed. Jaak Billet, Universitaire Pres Leuven, 1988, {{ISBN|90 6186 290 6}} p.321</ref>\n\n==Beginnings as a painter==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Tatlin, 1980.jpg|thumb|x210px|''Tatlin'', 1980, watercolour, coll. Royal Museum of Fine Arts, Antwerp]]\n\nAfter his studies in 1971, Vanriet\u2019s first gallery exhibition was at [[:nl:De Zwarte Panter|De Zwarte Panter]], directed by his former fellow student Adriaan Raemdonck.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">''Zo Krachtig Kan Verf Zijn'', Eric Rinckhout, De Morgen, 19 March 2015</ref> Immediately afterwards, a partnership was born with Jan Lens and his reputed gallery, Lens Fine Art, the most prestigious Belgian gallery at the time, which was to last for ten years.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  During this period, he developed into an excellent aquarellist and a few books were published: ''Maria Lecina'', ''Death in Venice'', ''Het teken van de hamster''.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nVanriet also developed as a writer. Collections of poetry were published by [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]] and for Flemish Radio 3 (now [[Klara (radio)|Radio Klara]]), he wrote a series of poems entitled ''Staat van Beleg'' (''State of Siege''), set to music by Bob Porter.<ref>''Gezichtsverlies' - beklijvende tentoonstelling van Jan Vanriet in jarig Museum Kazerne Dossin'', Jan Smets, Mechelen Blogt, 1 December 2013</ref> He wrote articles for weekly magazines such as ''[[Vrij Nederland]]'' and for the Dutch monthly magazine [[Avenue (magazine)|''Avenue'']], he edited a literary contribution from Belgium.<ref>''Jan Vanriet'', Jan Van Hove, De Standaard, Saturday 18 July 2015</ref>\n\nHe took part in the Menton Biennale and exhibited at [[:de:Galerie Brusberg|Galerie Brusberg]] in Hannover and [[:it:Galeria del Naviglio|Galleria del Naviglio]] in Milan, where he met the distinguished French art historian and critic [[Pierre Restany]], who became a fervent admirer of Vanriet's work.<ref>http://ruthleuchter.de/artists/jan-vanriet/#cv</ref> The [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Palais de Beaux-Arts (Bozar)]] in Brussels and the [[:de:Kunstverein Darmstadt|Kunstverein]] in Darmstadt exhibited the ''Death in Venice'' series.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>  The Royal Museum of Fine Arts in Antwerp purchased his work.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/> At this time, he began collaboration with the literary magazine ''Revolver'', designing its covers until 2010.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\n==Biennials==\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Bohemia, 1966.jpg|thumb|right|x220px|''Bohemia'', 1966, oil on paper, painted in Sovak\u2019s studio]]\nIn 1982, he joined the prestigious Galerie Isy Brachot in Brussels and Paris, where he presented 11 solo exhibitions in 10 years.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  [[Edward Lucie-Smith]] published a monograph on his work<ref>https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=178692</ref> and [[Pierre Restany]] wrote the text for Vanriet\u2019s first solo exhibition at Galerie Isy Brachot in Paris, ''l\u2019Etat du siege du regard''.<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/bibliography/</ref>  Vanriet was selected for the [[Sao Paulo Biennale]] (1979) and began a long series of exhibitions in California, mostly at the Wenger Gallery in San Diego, and later in Los Angeles.<ref>''Belgian Painter Vanriet brings his vision to San Diego'', Elise Miller, Los Angeles Times, 9 November 1981</ref><ref>''Realistically speaking, Vanriet's Watercolors are In'', Richard Reilly, The San Diego Union, 15 November 1981</ref>\n\nVanriet's work is in the collections of, among others, the [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]], the [[San Diego Museum of Art]] and the Hewlett Packard Corporation in Palo Alto.<ref name=\"webhosting2\">http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/biography/2/</ref> He was appointed Director of Antwerp\u2019s Hoboken Academy of Art.<ref>https://www.stedelijkonderwijs.be/academie-hoboken-bk/partners-138</ref> He left the school in 1999.\n\nThe Ministry of Flemish Culture published a monograph of his work and selected him to represent Belgium at the [[Venice Biennale]] (1984) together with Karel Dierickx and [[Jan Fabre]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">''Coming Together to Close'', Flanders Today, 12 May 2010</ref> Vanriet was invited to participate in the Olympiad of Arts in Seoul (1989)<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">''Toues les \u00e9mois de la vie en peinture'', Claude Lorent, La Libre, 13 February 2015</ref>  and his monumental canvas ''Compte \u00e0 r\u00e8gler'' is now in the [[National Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art|National Museum of Contemporary Art in Seoul]].<ref>http://cobra.canvas.be/cm/cobra/kunst/1.1948634</ref> In between, he stayed two summers in New York to work in [[Bernar Venet]]\u2019s studio, where his friend artist [[David Levine]] often came to visit him.<ref>''Attention ! Jan Vanriet a demand\u00e9 express\u00e9ment de gommer la plaque de rue avec Photoshop !'', Le Soir, Saturday 8 October 2011</ref> Commissions for portraits were awarded by the New York lawyer and art patron [[:fr:Harry Torczyner (avocat)|Harry Torczyner]], the Belgian Parliament and the University of Louvain (portrait of rector [[Pieter De Somer]] for the Ceremony Hall).<ref name=\"webhosting2\"/>\n\nIn the context of Antwerp 93 (Antwerp as [[European Capital of Culture|European Cultural Capital 1993]]), the Elzenveld Art Centre opened new gallery areas with a large-scale exhibition of Vanriet\u2019s recent work.<ref name=\"webhosting2\"/>  This was not his only contribution to this festival year: he also painted the entrance hall ceilings in the restored [[Bourla Theatre]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/>\n\n1990 ''The Special Prize'' at the Art Festival Seoul, together with [[John Chamberlain (sculptor)|John Chamberlain]] and [[Mimmo Rotella]].\n\n==Closing the Royal Museum of Fine Arts, Antwerp==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Closing TIme, 2010,.jpg|thumb|right|x200px|''Closing Time'', 2010: Vanriet\u2019s work with paintings by Fontana and Antonello da Messina]]\n\nIn the mid-1990s, Vanriet finished a series of 50 portraits as well as ''Volgens Johannes'', 35 large works on [[Korean paper|Korean ''hanji'' paper]], inspired by the [[Gospel of John]], for which Dutch poet [[:nl:Benno Barnard|Benno Barnard]] wrote an epic text.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/> An exhibition was held at the Veranneman Foundation in [[Kruishoutem]], together with a show by French abstract painter [[Pierre Soulages]].<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/exhibitions/</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Jan Vanriet renewed his partnership with De Zwarte Panter Gallery in Antwerp.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>  New works were collected by the [[McNay Art Museum]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]],<ref>https://www.kazernedossin.eu/NL/Bezoek/Publieksprogramma/Tijdelijke-tentoonstelling/Archief/Jan-Vanriet-Gezichtsverlies</ref> and by Deutsche Bank, Royal Belge, Cr\u00e9dit Lyonnais and Z\u00fcrich Insurance. The [[:nl:Stedelijk Prentenkabinet|Stedelijk Prentenkabinet]] at the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]] in Antwerp also procured preparatory studies for Johannes.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nIn 2001 he received the Van Acker Prize in Bruges (previous laureats: [[Hugo Claus]], [[Frans Masereel]], [[Roger Raveel]]).\n\nIn May 2004, the {{ill|Lippisches Landesmuseum|de}} in [[Detmold]] ([[Germany]]) exhibited ''Transport'', paintings 1999-2004, many of them inspired by the tragic events in World War II.<ref>http://galeriezwarthuis.be/nl/tentoonstellingen/black</ref>  For Vanriet this is not an unusual theme; his parents and other members of his family engaged in the resistance against Nazi invaders, but they were made prisoner and deported to the concentration camps of [[Mauthausen]] and [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>''Many Jews refused to discuss the Holocaust - it is too painful'', Izvestiya, 27 January 2015</ref>\n\nA year later, in 2005, Vanriet travelled to Israel for the hanging of his triptych ''Nathan the Wise'' in the historical building of the [[Jerusalem International YMCA]], designed by [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]]. The Flemish Government and other governmental institutions donated Vanriet's work as their official present on the occasion of the state visits of [[Jorge Sampaio]], President of Portugal, [[Viktor Yushchenko]], President of Ukraine, [[Romano Prodi]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]], both Presidents of the European Commission, Jack Lang, French Minister of Culture and more.<ref>''Ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9'', Het Nieuwsblad, Luke van Bakel, 21 October 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Paul Huvenne, the director of the [[Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp|Royal Museum of Fine Arts]] in Antwerp invited Jan Vanriet to \u2018close\u2019 the museum, where enormous works of renovation were to start. With the exhibition ''Closing Time'' he proposed a selection of 170 masterpieces from the collection, including works by [[Rubens]], [[Van Eyck]], [[Van Dyck]], [[Titian]], [[Cranach]], [[James Ensor|Ensor]] and [[Amedeo Modigliani|Modigliani]] in confrontation with a retrospective selection of his own work.<ref>''Coming Together To Close'', Anna Jenkinson, Flanders Today, 12 May 2010</ref>  88,000 visitors attended.<ref>http://artbahrain.org/web/?p=3355</ref>\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Moszek, 2011.jpg|thumb|right|x333px|''Moszek'', 2011, watercolour, coll. British Museum London]]\n\nThat same year, Vanriet painted the official portrait of the departing cardinal [[Godfried Danneels]] for the Archbishop's palace in Malines.<ref>http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/957/Binnenland/article/detail/1069786/2010/02/19/Danneels-onthult-revolutionair-staatsieportret.dhtml</ref> In 2013, the public was stunned by Vanriet's series of Jewish deportees from Belgium to Auschwitz. The exhibition ''Losing Face'' was shown at the Museum [[Kazerne Dossin]] in Malines.<ref>''Rendre un visage aux victimes dez nazis'', Guy Duplat, La Libre, 28 November 2013</ref> Belgian press proclaimed ''Losing Face'' as one of Europe's major exhibitions.<ref>''Een gezicht voor de doden'', Jan Van Hove, De Standaard, 25 November 2013</ref>  The prominent Flemish author [[Stefan Hertmans]] and the Hungarian novelist [[Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d]] contributed to the accompanying publication.<ref>''Dit is mijn monument'', Wim Daeninck, CITT, 30 November 2011</ref>\n\n==Newest projects==\n\n''Closed Doors'' was the inaugural exhibition of Roberto Polo Gallery in Brussels, in November 2012.<ref>''Group Shoes and guitar heroes. This weekend in Belgium'', The Word Magazine, 22 November 2011</ref> It started an intense and inspiring collaboration between the artist and the American art historian, theorist and gallerist.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  In February 2015, Vanriet\u2019s second solo show, ''Vanity'', opened the new extended gallery, which virtually doubled its size.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/>\n\nThis collaboration brought ''Losing Face'' to the [[Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center|Jewish Museum and Tolerance Centre]] in Moscow (January 2015), where President [[Vladimir Putin]] visited the show.<ref>Holocaust Exhibit Gives Faces to the Victims, Layli Foroudi, The Moscow Times, 28 January 2015</ref> This exhibition was designed by the architect [[Sergei Tchoban]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In May 2015, the [[National Museum, Gdansk|National Museum in Gdansk]] proposed ''Song of Destiny'', a survey show of Vanriet\u2019s paintings from 1986-2014.<ref>''Dankzij Luk Tuymans kan figuratieve kunst weer. Ik zou hem eens moeten trakteren'', Mark Schaevers, Humo, 9 June 2015</ref> In the accompanying book, Polish poet [[Adam Zagajewski]] made an appearance. The National Museum in Gdansk acquired 2 of his paintings in 2014. The same year, 5 of Vanriet\u2019s watercolours entered the collection of the [[British Museum]] in London, and The Museum of the History of Polish Jews in Warsaw acquired 2 of his paintings. The New Art Gallery Walsall acquired 2 of his paintings in 2015. In January 2016, Vanriet's UK premiere took place with a survey show, ''The Music Boy'' at the [[New Art Gallery Walsall]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  The eponymous exhibition catalogue contains essays by Charlotte Mullins, [[Andrew Graham-Dixon]] and Martin Herbert.<ref>http://www.dezwartepanter.com/vanriet.html</ref> Hollands Diep, the new publishing house of former Bezige Bij director [[:nl:Robbert Ammerlaan|Robbert Ammerlaan]], publishes Moederland (Motherland), Vanriet\u2019s recent poetry. In September 2016, Vanriet, along with 15 renowned painters, 7 other Belgians and 8 Americans, participated in the Brussels manifesto exhibition 'Painting After Postmodernism', curated by Barbara Rose, a show also presented in Malaga and in the Caserta Palace near Napels.\nIn 2018 he showed his series 'Ex Voto' at De Zwarte Panter<ref>http://www.dezwartepanter.com/</ref> and published 'Radeloos geluk\u2019 (Desperate Happiness, published by Hollands Diep<ref name=\"hollandsdiep.nl\">https://www.hollandsdiep.nl/</ref>), 580 pages of autobiographical essays, nominated for the Bookspot Prize for Literature in the Netherlands.  In 2019 Po\u00ebziecentrum<ref name=\"poeziecentrum.be\">https://www.poeziecentrum.be/</ref> publishes an overview of Vanriet\u2019s poetry, \u2018Kouwe kleren\u2019 (Cold Clothes).\n\n==Public spaces and applied art==\n\nVanriet's ceiling painting at the [[Bourla Theatre]] opened doors for more commissioned work in public spaces.  Best known are ''To The Energy!'', a triptych for energy producer Electrabel,<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/collections/</ref> ''The Haunted Domain'', an integrated mural 110 metres in length for the new headquarters of Kredietbank in Brussels,<ref>http://cultuur.knokke-heist.be/event/zondagbabbel-met-jan-vanriet-over-poezie-en-schilderkunst</ref> and two even larger projects for Roularta Publishing and for Metro De Brouck\u00e8re, both located in Brussels.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/><ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/monumentale-werken/roularta-media-centre-1/</ref>\n\nSince 1987 Jan Vanriet has designed the stage for Raamtheater,<ref>http://home.scarlet.be/~tsd15948/rt/medewerkers/vanriet.htm</ref> Geletterde Mensen<ref>''Gevoelige Geletterde Mensen met Van Dis, Mortier en Moeyaert'', Eva Berghmans, De Standaard, 29 March 2004</ref> and the international literary tours of Behoud de Begeerte in Madrid, Barcelona, London, Amsterdam and Aix-en-Provence, for VRT (Flemish Television) and the [[:nl:Koninklijke Vlaamse Schouwburg|Royal Flemish Theatre Brussels (KVS)]].<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nHe was commissioned by newspaper [[De Morgen]] to illustrate a novel daily by [[Hugo Claus]],<ref>''Jan Vanriet'', Humo Magazine, 9 June 2015</ref> and the latter wrote poems for ten of Vanriet\u2019s etchings, published in the book ''The Ape In Efese''. Publishers in the Netherlands and France ([[De Bezige Bij]], Balland, [[Le Seuil]]) illustrated the covers of their novels with his work.<ref>http://www.galeries.nl/mnkunstenaar.asp?artistnr=8452&vane=1&em=&meer=&sessionti=1056628228</ref> He has also designed posters, such as for the Flemish Bookfair 1999.<ref>''Vanriet ontwerpt affiche Boekenbeurs'', Peter Haex, Gazet Van Antwerpen, 22 September 1999</ref>  From December 2000, he began a weekly drawing for ZENO, the essay supplement of the newspaper [[De Morgen]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In 2003 he started his own column ''EenOog'' in ''Weekend Knack''<ref>http://www.quovadisart.be/?p=307</ref> and in 2008, he wrote and illustrated a weekly column, ''Joetoeb'', on art & culture for De Morgen Magazine.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nIn 2004, Vanriet was commissioned to create a mural titled \"The City Moves in the Palm of My hand\" for the [[De Brouck\u00e8re metro station]] in [[Brussels]]. The artwork was printed on finished edge panels from [[PolyVision (company)|PolyVision]].<ref>{{cite web|title=De Brouckere Metro Station|url=https://polyvision.com/about/our-surfaces/projects/de-brouckere-metro-station|website=PolyVision|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> In 2018 he designed a stained glass window for The Holland College in Louvain.\n\nIn 2007, the Dutch author [[Cees Nooteboom]] invited Vanriet to collaborate on a book with his short stories, ''Red Rain'', first published by [[Suhrkamp]] in Germany. Afterwards the publishing house returned to Vanriet for the illustration of a series covers for other Nooteboom books on the occasion of his 75th birthday.<ref>http://www.maxpam.nl/2007/11/de-afdeling-opschepperij-slaat-weer-toe/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 1971, he married Simone Lenaerts, with whom he has two sons, Bram and Menno, and a daughter Eva.<ref>''The International Who's Who 2004'', Europa Publications, 2003, {{ISBN|1 85743 217 7}}, p.1729</ref><ref>http://hildevancanneyt.blogspot.co.uk/2010/05/interview-met-jan-vanriet.html</ref>  Simone Lenaerts made her debut as a novelist in 2009, won the Flemish Debut Prize and was nominated for the Academica Prize in the Netherlands.<ref>http://www.citybooks.eu/nl/artiest/p/simone-lenaerts</ref> They live and work in Antwerp.<ref>''Artnews'', April 1982</ref> and from 1990 until 2014, they partly lived in the south of France, in [[Crillon le Brave]]. In 2017 he was elected as a member of the [[European Academy of Sciences and Arts]] in Salzburg.\n\n==Literature==\n\n2019 ''Kouwe kleren'', Po\u00ebziecentrum<ref name=\"poeziecentrum.be\"/><br>\n2018 ''Radeloos geluk'', Hollands Diep<ref name=\"hollandsdiep.nl\"/><br>\n2016 ''Moederland'', Hollands Diep<br>\n2014 ''Oud zeer'', Plantin Instituut voor Typografie<br>\n2012 ''Leegstand'', [[De Bezige Bij]] Antwerpen<br>\n2008 ''Stormlicht'', Wagner & van Santen<br>\n1984 ''Geen hond die brood lust'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1979 ''Staat van beleg'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1974 ''Bella Ciao'', Ontwikkeling<br>\n1973 ''Vast Tapijt'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1971 ''Met de Ramblers uit vissen'', Revolver<br>\n1969 ''Met gehavend gemoed'', Yang\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n''Ex Voto'', '''Eric Rinckhout''', De Zwarte Panter, 2018<br>\n''The Music Boy'', '''Andrew Graham-Dixon, Martin Herbert and Charlotte Mullins''', The New Art Gallery Walsall, 2016<br>\n''Song of Destiny'', '''Paul Huvenne, Adam Zagajewski and Zofia Machnica''', National Museum Gdansk, 2015<br>\n''Losing Face'', '''Stefan Hertmans and Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d''', Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center Moscow, 2015<br>\n''Omens'', De Zwarte Panter, 2015<br>\n''Vanity, Jan Vanriet'', '''Charlotte Mullins''',  Lannoo, 2015<br>\n''Losing Face'', '''Stefan Hertmans and Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d''', Ludion 2013<br>\n''Closed Doors'', '''Eric Rinckhout''', Roberto Polo Gallery, 2012<br>\n''Closing Time'', '''Maarten Doorman en Eric Rinckhout''', Ludion | De Bezige Bij, 2010<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, Parcours 1966-2008'', '''Marc Ruyters''', Snoeck, 2008<br>\n''Een Winterreise'', '''Cees Nooteboom & Jan Vanriet''', Literarte, 2007<br>\n''De Testamenten'', Jan Vanriet, with text by '''Marc Ruyters and Luc Devisscher''', Davidsfonds Uitgeverij, 2005<br>\n''Transport'', '''Cees Nooteboom and Vera Scheef''', Lippisches Landesmuseum Detmold, 2004<br>\n''Transport'', '''Bernard Dewulf''', Art Concern, 2002<br>\n''De reiziger is blind'', '''Jean Pierre Rondas''', De Geus, 2001<br>\n''Caf\u00e9 Aurora'', '''Stefan Hertmans''', De Geus, 2000<br>\n''Jan Vanriet'', '''Freddy de Vree''', Lannoo, 1996<br>\n''Mati\u00e8re et M\u00e9moire'', '''Pierre Restany''', Centrum Elzenveld, 1993<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, or the Subtle Disruption'', '''Wim Meeuwis''', Internationale Culturele Samenwerking, Biennale di Venezia, 1984<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, L\u2019\u00e9tat de si\u00e8ge du regard'', '''Pierre Restany''', Galerie Isy Brachot, Paris, 1983<br>\n''Jan Vanriet'', '''Edward Lucie-Smith''', Uitgeverij Manteau, Antwerpen, & van Gennep, 1982\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.janvanriet.com/ Jan Vanriet - Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160109200851/http://simonelenaerts.be/ Simone Lenaerts - Official website]\n* [http://www.hollandsdiep.nl/ Hollands Diep]\n* [http://www.mennovanriet.be/ Menno Vanriet - Official website]\n* [http://www.caviarcontent.com/losangeles/directors/bram-vanriet/ Bram Vanriet - Caviar Content]\n* [http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/jan-vanriet-the-music-boy/ Jan Vanriet 'The Music Boy' at The New Art Gallery Walsall]\n* [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?searchText=vanriet/ Jan Vanriet at The British Museum]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vanriet, Jan}}\n[[Category:Flemish painters]]\n[[Category:Flemish poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Jan Vanriet\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = Photo of the artist\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age |df=yes|1948|2|21|}}\n| birth_place   = [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]]\n| nationality = Belgian\n| field         = Painting, Poetry\n| training      = [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Antwerp]]\n}}\n\n'''Jan Vanriet''', real name Jan Louis Lucien Vanriet, (21 February 1948) is a [[Belgian]] ([[Flemish]]) painter and poet.<ref name=\"webhosting1\">http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/biography/</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet.jpg|thumb|left|x220px]]\nJan Vanriet was born in Antwerp and attended the Royal Atheneum of Hoboken where the art critic and promotor [[:nl:Marcel van Jole|Marcel van Jole]] was one of his teachers.<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/category/blog/</ref>  In 1965, while visiting Prague, he met the avant-garde graphic artist [[:de:Pravoslav Sovak|Pravoslav Sovak]], who at 22 years older, became his mentor.  The following year Vanriet was invited to the artist's studio in South Bohemia, where he painted a series of landscapes. Their friendship continues today.\n\nIn 1968, Vanriet started painting studies at the [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Fine Arts in Antwerp]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">''Jan Vanriet: It may be that people are able to learn lessons from the past'', Darya Palatkina, The Art Newspaper, Russia</ref>   As a young art student and a debuting poet, he became deeply involved in writers' actions against literary censorship in Belgium, actions that became very famous when he organised a Protest Read-In at the Majestic Theatre in Antwerp, with 40 authors on stage and an audience of over 1000. A second Read-In was organised at [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Palais des Beaux-Arts in Brussels]] (Bozar). It was here that he met his future wife, Simone Lenaerts.<ref>''Jarig in mijn schitterend woord: opstellen over Hugues C. Pernath'', Academia Press, 2012, {{ISBN|978 90 382 2029 1}}, p.69</ref>\n\nIn 1971, he became the youngest member of the editing council of the influential political monthly ''De Nieuwe Maand'' (''The New Month''), a group of ambitious politicians from catholic and socialist parties, amongst them, the later prime ministers [[Jean-Luc Dehaene]] and [[Wilfried Martens]], and European Commissar [[Karel van Miert]].<ref>''Tussen bescherming en verovering: sociologen en historici over zuilvorming'', ed. Jaak Billet, Universitaire Pres Leuven, 1988, {{ISBN|90 6186 290 6}} p.321</ref>\n\n==Beginnings as a painter==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Tatlin, 1980.jpg|thumb|x210px|''Tatlin'', 1980, watercolour, coll. Royal Museum of Fine Arts, Antwerp]]\n\nAfter his studies in 1971, Vanriet\u2019s first gallery exhibition was at [[:nl:De Zwarte Panter|De Zwarte Panter]], directed by his former fellow student Adriaan Raemdonck.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">''Zo Krachtig Kan Verf Zijn'', Eric Rinckhout, De Morgen, 19 March 2015</ref> Immediately afterwards, a partnership was born with Jan Lens and his reputed gallery, Lens Fine Art, the most prestigious Belgian gallery at the time, which was to last for ten years.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  During this period, he developed into an excellent aquarellist and a few books were published: ''Maria Lecina'', ''Death in Venice'', ''Het teken van de hamster''.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nVanriet also developed as a writer. Collections of poetry were published by [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]] and for Flemish Radio 3 (now [[Klara (radio)|Radio Klara]]), he wrote a series of poems entitled ''Staat van Beleg'' (''State of Siege''), set to music by Bob Porter.<ref>''Gezichtsverlies' - beklijvende tentoonstelling van Jan Vanriet in jarig Museum Kazerne Dossin'', Jan Smets, Mechelen Blogt, 1 December 2013</ref> He wrote articles for weekly magazines such as ''[[Vrij Nederland]]'' and for the Dutch monthly magazine [[Avenue (magazine)|''Avenue'']], he edited a literary contribution from Belgium.<ref>''Jan Vanriet'', Jan Van Hove, De Standaard, Saturday 18 July 2015</ref>\n\nHe took part in the Menton Biennale and exhibited at [[:de:Galerie Brusberg|Galerie Brusberg]] in Hannover and [[:it:Galeria del Naviglio|Galleria del Naviglio]] in Milan, where he met the distinguished French art historian and critic [[Pierre Restany]], who became a fervent admirer of Vanriet's work.<ref>http://ruthleuchter.de/artists/jan-vanriet/#cv</ref> The [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Palais de Beaux-Arts (Bozar)]] in Brussels and the [[:de:Kunstverein Darmstadt|Kunstverein]] in Darmstadt exhibited the ''Death in Venice'' series.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>  The Royal Museum of Fine Arts in Antwerp purchased his work.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/> At this time, he began collaboration with the literary magazine ''Revolver'', designing its covers until 2010.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\n==Biennials==\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Bohemia, 1966.jpg|thumb|right|x220px|''Bohemia'', 1966, oil on paper, painted in Sovak\u2019s studio]]\nIn 1982, he joined the prestigious Galerie Isy Brachot in Brussels and Paris, where he presented 11 solo exhibitions in 10 years.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  [[Edward Lucie-Smith]] published a monograph on his work<ref>https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=178692</ref> and [[Pierre Restany]] wrote the text for Vanriet\u2019s first solo exhibition at Galerie Isy Brachot in Paris, ''l\u2019Etat du siege du regard''.<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/bibliography/</ref>  Vanriet was selected for the [[Sao Paulo Biennale]] (1979) and began a long series of exhibitions in California, mostly at the Wenger Gallery in San Diego, and later in Los Angeles.<ref>''Belgian Painter Vanriet brings his vision to San Diego'', Elise Miller, Los Angeles Times, 9 November 1981</ref><ref>''Realistically speaking, Vanriet's Watercolors are In'', Richard Reilly, The San Diego Union, 15 November 1981</ref>\n\nVanriet's work is in the collections of, among others, the [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]], the [[San Diego Museum of Art]] and the Hewlett Packard Corporation in Palo Alto.<ref name=\"webhosting2\">http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/biography/2/</ref> He was appointed Director of Antwerp\u2019s Hoboken Academy of Art.<ref>https://www.stedelijkonderwijs.be/academie-hoboken-bk/partners-138</ref> He left the school in 1999.\n\nThe Ministry of Flemish Culture published a monograph of his work and selected him to represent Belgium at the [[Venice Biennale]] (1984) together with Karel Dierickx and [[Jan Fabre]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">''Coming Together to Close'', Flanders Today, 12 May 2010</ref> Vanriet was invited to participate in the Olympiad of Arts in Seoul (1989)<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">''Toues les \u00e9mois de la vie en peinture'', Claude Lorent, La Libre, 13 February 2015</ref>  and his monumental canvas ''Compte \u00e0 r\u00e8gler'' is now in the [[National Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art|National Museum of Contemporary Art in Seoul]].<ref>http://cobra.canvas.be/cm/cobra/kunst/1.1948634</ref> In between, he stayed two summers in New York to work in [[Bernar Venet]]\u2019s studio, where his friend artist [[David Levine]] often came to visit him.<ref>''Attention ! Jan Vanriet a demand\u00e9 express\u00e9ment de gommer la plaque de rue avec Photoshop !'', Le Soir, Saturday 8 October 2011</ref> Commissions for portraits were awarded by the New York lawyer and art patron [[:fr:Harry Torczyner (avocat)|Harry Torczyner]], the Belgian Parliament and the University of Louvain (portrait of rector [[Pieter De Somer]] for the Ceremony Hall).<ref name=\"webhosting2\"/>\n\nIn the context of Antwerp 93 (Antwerp as [[European Capital of Culture|European Cultural Capital 1993]]), the Elzenveld Art Centre opened new gallery areas with a large-scale exhibition of Vanriet\u2019s recent work.<ref name=\"webhosting2\"/>  This was not his only contribution to this festival year: he also painted the entrance hall ceilings in the restored [[Bourla Theatre]].<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/>\n\n1990 ''The Special Prize'' at the Art Festival Seoul, together with [[John Chamberlain (sculptor)|John Chamberlain]] and [[Mimmo Rotella]].\n\n==Closing the Royal Museum of Fine Arts, Antwerp==\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Closing TIme, 2010,.jpg|thumb|right|x200px|''Closing Time'', 2010: Vanriet\u2019s work with paintings by Fontana and Antonello da Messina]]\n\nIn the mid-1990s, Vanriet finished a series of 50 portraits as well as ''Volgens Johannes'', 35 large works on [[Korean paper|Korean ''hanji'' paper]], inspired by the [[Gospel of John]], for which Dutch poet [[:nl:Benno Barnard|Benno Barnard]] wrote an epic text.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/> An exhibition was held at the Veranneman Foundation in [[Kruishoutem]], together with a show by French abstract painter [[Pierre Soulages]].<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/exhibitions/</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Jan Vanriet renewed his partnership with De Zwarte Panter Gallery in Antwerp.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>  New works were collected by the [[McNay Art Museum]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]],<ref>https://www.kazernedossin.eu/NL/Bezoek/Publieksprogramma/Tijdelijke-tentoonstelling/Archief/Jan-Vanriet-Gezichtsverlies</ref> and by Deutsche Bank, Royal Belge, Cr\u00e9dit Lyonnais and Z\u00fcrich Insurance. The [[:nl:Stedelijk Prentenkabinet|Stedelijk Prentenkabinet]] at the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]] in Antwerp also procured preparatory studies for Johannes.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nIn 2001 he received the Van Acker Prize in Bruges (previous laureats: [[Hugo Claus]], [[Frans Masereel]], [[Roger Raveel]]).\n\nIn May 2004, the {{ill|Lippisches Landesmuseum|de}} in [[Detmold]] ([[Germany]]) exhibited ''Transport'', paintings 1999-2004, many of them inspired by the tragic events in World War II.<ref>http://galeriezwarthuis.be/nl/tentoonstellingen/black</ref>  For Vanriet this is not an unusual theme; his parents and other members of his family engaged in the resistance against Nazi invaders, but they were made prisoner and deported to the concentration camps of [[Mauthausen]] and [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>''Many Jews refused to discuss the Holocaust - it is too painful'', Izvestiya, 27 January 2015</ref>\n\nA year later, in 2005, Vanriet travelled to Israel for the hanging of his triptych ''Nathan the Wise'' in the historical building of the [[Jerusalem International YMCA]], designed by [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]]. The Flemish Government and other governmental institutions donated Vanriet's work as their official present on the occasion of the state visits of [[Jorge Sampaio]], President of Portugal, [[Viktor Yushchenko]], President of Ukraine, [[Romano Prodi]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]], both Presidents of the European Commission, Jack Lang, French Minister of Culture and more.<ref>''Ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9 ol\u00e9'', Het Nieuwsblad, Luke van Bakel, 21 October 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Paul Huvenne, the director of the [[Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp|Royal Museum of Fine Arts]] in Antwerp invited Jan Vanriet to \u2018close\u2019 the museum, where enormous works of renovation were to start. With the exhibition ''Closing Time'' he proposed a selection of 170 masterpieces from the collection, including works by [[Rubens]], [[Van Eyck]], [[Van Dyck]], [[Titian]], [[Cranach]], [[James Ensor|Ensor]] and [[Amedeo Modigliani|Modigliani]] in confrontation with a retrospective selection of his own work.<ref>''Coming Together To Close'', Anna Jenkinson, Flanders Today, 12 May 2010</ref>  88,000 visitors attended.<ref>http://artbahrain.org/web/?p=3355</ref>\n\n[[File:Jan Vanriet, Moszek, 2011.jpg|thumb|right|x333px|''Moszek'', 2011, watercolour, coll. British Museum London]]\n\nThat same year, Vanriet painted the official portrait of the departing cardinal [[Godfried Danneels]] for the Archbishop's palace in Malines.<ref>http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/957/Binnenland/article/detail/1069786/2010/02/19/Danneels-onthult-revolutionair-staatsieportret.dhtml</ref> In 2013, the public was stunned by Vanriet's series of Jewish deportees from Belgium to Auschwitz. The exhibition ''Losing Face'' was shown at the Museum [[Kazerne Dossin]] in Malines.<ref>''Rendre un visage aux victimes dez nazis'', Guy Duplat, La Libre, 28 November 2013</ref> Belgian press proclaimed ''Losing Face'' as one of Europe's major exhibitions.<ref>''Een gezicht voor de doden'', Jan Van Hove, De Standaard, 25 November 2013</ref>  The prominent Flemish author [[Stefan Hertmans]] and the Hungarian novelist [[Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d]] contributed to the accompanying publication.<ref>''Dit is mijn monument'', Wim Daeninck, CITT, 30 November 2011</ref>\n\n==Newest projects==\n\n''Closed Doors'' was the inaugural exhibition of Roberto Polo Gallery in Brussels, in November 2012.<ref>''Group Shoes and guitar heroes. This weekend in Belgium'', The Word Magazine, 22 November 2011</ref> It started an intense and inspiring collaboration between the artist and the American art historian, theorist and gallerist.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  In February 2015, Vanriet\u2019s second solo show, ''Vanity'', opened the new extended gallery, which virtually doubled its size.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/>\n\nThis collaboration brought ''Losing Face'' to the [[Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center|Jewish Museum and Tolerance Centre]] in Moscow (January 2015), where President [[Vladimir Putin]] visited the show.<ref>Holocaust Exhibit Gives Faces to the Victims, Layli Foroudi, The Moscow Times, 28 January 2015</ref> This exhibition was designed by the architect [[Sergei Tchoban]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In May 2015, the [[National Museum, Gdansk|National Museum in Gdansk]] proposed ''Song of Destiny'', a survey show of Vanriet\u2019s paintings from 1986-2014.<ref>''Dankzij Luk Tuymans kan figuratieve kunst weer. Ik zou hem eens moeten trakteren'', Mark Schaevers, Humo, 9 June 2015</ref> In the accompanying book, Polish poet [[Adam Zagajewski]] made an appearance. The National Museum in Gdansk acquired 2 of his paintings in 2014. The same year, 5 of Vanriet\u2019s watercolours entered the collection of the [[British Museum]] in London, and The Museum of the History of Polish Jews in Warsaw acquired 2 of his paintings. The New Art Gallery Walsall acquired 2 of his paintings in 2015. In January 2016, Vanriet's UK premiere took place with a survey show, ''The Music Boy'' at the [[New Art Gallery Walsall]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  The eponymous exhibition catalogue contains essays by Charlotte Mullins, [[Andrew Graham-Dixon]] and Martin Herbert.<ref>http://www.dezwartepanter.com/vanriet.html</ref> Hollands Diep, the new publishing house of former Bezige Bij director [[:nl:Robbert Ammerlaan|Robbert Ammerlaan]], publishes Moederland (Motherland), Vanriet\u2019s recent poetry. In September 2016, Vanriet, along with 15 renowned painters, 7 other Belgians and 8 Americans, participated in the Brussels manifesto exhibition 'Painting After Postmodernism', curated by Barbara Rose, a show also presented in Malaga and in the Caserta Palace near Napels.\nIn 2018 he showed his series 'Ex Voto' at De Zwarte Panter<ref>http://www.dezwartepanter.com/</ref> and published 'Radeloos geluk\u2019 (Desperate Happiness, published by Hollands Diep<ref>https://www.hollandsdiep.nl/</ref>), 580 pages of autobiographical essays, nominated for the Bookspot Prize for Literature in the Netherlands.  In 2019 Po\u00ebziecentrum<ref>https://www.poeziecentrum.be/</ref> publishes an overview of Vanriet\u2019s poetry, \u2018Kouwe kleren\u2019 (Cold Clothes).\n\n==Public spaces and applied art==\n\nVanriet's ceiling painting at the [[Bourla Theatre]] opened doors for more commissioned work in public spaces.  Best known are ''To The Energy!'', a triptych for energy producer Electrabel,<ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/en/collections/</ref> ''The Haunted Domain'', an integrated mural 110 metres in length for the new headquarters of Kredietbank in Brussels,<ref>http://cultuur.knokke-heist.be/event/zondagbabbel-met-jan-vanriet-over-poezie-en-schilderkunst</ref> and two even larger projects for Roularta Publishing and for Metro De Brouck\u00e8re, both located in Brussels.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/><ref>http://janvanrietcom.webhosting.be/monumentale-werken/roularta-media-centre-1/</ref>\n\nSince 1987 Jan Vanriet has designed the stage for Raamtheater,<ref>http://home.scarlet.be/~tsd15948/rt/medewerkers/vanriet.htm</ref> Geletterde Mensen<ref>''Gevoelige Geletterde Mensen met Van Dis, Mortier en Moeyaert'', Eva Berghmans, De Standaard, 29 March 2004</ref> and the international literary tours of Behoud de Begeerte in Madrid, Barcelona, London, Amsterdam and Aix-en-Provence, for VRT (Flemish Television) and the [[:nl:Koninklijke Vlaamse Schouwburg|Royal Flemish Theatre Brussels (KVS)]].<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nHe was commissioned by newspaper [[De Morgen]] to illustrate a novel daily by [[Hugo Claus]],<ref>''Jan Vanriet'', Humo Magazine, 9 June 2015</ref> and the latter wrote poems for ten of Vanriet\u2019s etchings, published in the book ''The Ape In Efese''. Publishers in the Netherlands and France ([[De Bezige Bij]], Balland, [[Le Seuil]]) illustrated the covers of their novels with his work.<ref>http://www.galeries.nl/mnkunstenaar.asp?artistnr=8452&vane=1&em=&meer=&sessionti=1056628228</ref> He has also designed posters, such as for the Flemish Bookfair 1999.<ref>''Vanriet ontwerpt affiche Boekenbeurs'', Peter Haex, Gazet Van Antwerpen, 22 September 1999</ref>  From December 2000, he began a weekly drawing for ZENO, the essay supplement of the newspaper [[De Morgen]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In 2003 he started his own column ''EenOog'' in ''Weekend Knack''<ref>http://www.quovadisart.be/?p=307</ref> and in 2008, he wrote and illustrated a weekly column, ''Joetoeb'', on art & culture for De Morgen Magazine.<ref name=\"webhosting1\"/>\n\nIn 2004, Vanriet was commissioned to create a mural titled \"The City Moves in the Palm of My hand\" for the [[De Brouck\u00e8re metro station]] in [[Brussels]]. The artwork was printed on finished edge panels from [[PolyVision (company)|PolyVision]].<ref>{{cite web|title=De Brouckere Metro Station|url=https://polyvision.com/about/our-surfaces/projects/de-brouckere-metro-station|website=PolyVision|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> In 2018 he designed a stained glass window for The Holland College in Louvain.\n\nIn 2007, the Dutch author [[Cees Nooteboom]] invited Vanriet to collaborate on a book with his short stories, ''Red Rain'', first published by [[Suhrkamp]] in Germany. Afterwards the publishing house returned to Vanriet for the illustration of a series covers for other Nooteboom books on the occasion of his 75th birthday.<ref>http://www.maxpam.nl/2007/11/de-afdeling-opschepperij-slaat-weer-toe/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 1971, he married Simone Lenaerts, with whom he has two sons, Bram and Menno, and a daughter Eva.<ref>''The International Who's Who 2004'', Europa Publications, 2003, {{ISBN|1 85743 217 7}}, p.1729</ref><ref>http://hildevancanneyt.blogspot.co.uk/2010/05/interview-met-jan-vanriet.html</ref>  Simone Lenaerts made her debut as a novelist in 2009, won the Flemish Debut Prize and was nominated for the Academica Prize in the Netherlands.<ref>http://www.citybooks.eu/nl/artiest/p/simone-lenaerts</ref> They live and work in Antwerp.<ref>''Artnews'', April 1982</ref> and from 1990 until 2014, they partly lived in the south of France, in [[Crillon le Brave]]. In 2017 he was elected as a member of the [[European Academy of Sciences and Arts]] in Salzburg.\n\n==Literature==\n\n2019 ''Kouwe kleren'', Po\u00ebziecentrum<ref>https://www.poeziecentrum.be/</ref><br>\n2018 ''Radeloos geluk'', Hollands Diep<ref>https://www.hollandsdiep.nl/</ref><br>\n2016 ''Moederland'', Hollands Diep<br>\n2014 ''Oud zeer'', Plantin Instituut voor Typografie<br>\n2012 ''Leegstand'', [[De Bezige Bij]] Antwerpen<br>\n2008 ''Stormlicht'', Wagner & van Santen<br>\n1984 ''Geen hond die brood lust'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1979 ''Staat van beleg'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1974 ''Bella Ciao'', Ontwikkeling<br>\n1973 ''Vast Tapijt'', [[Manteau (publisher)|Manteau]]<br>\n1971 ''Met de Ramblers uit vissen'', Revolver<br>\n1969 ''Met gehavend gemoed'', Yang\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n''Ex Voto'', '''Eric Rinckhout''', De Zwarte Panter, 2018<br>\n''The Music Boy'', '''Andrew Graham-Dixon, Martin Herbert and Charlotte Mullins''', The New Art Gallery Walsall, 2016<br>\n''Song of Destiny'', '''Paul Huvenne, Adam Zagajewski and Zofia Machnica''', National Museum Gdansk, 2015<br>\n''Losing Face'', '''Stefan Hertmans and Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d''', Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center Moscow, 2015<br>\n''Omens'', De Zwarte Panter, 2015<br>\n''Vanity, Jan Vanriet'', '''Charlotte Mullins''',  Lannoo, 2015<br>\n''Losing Face'', '''Stefan Hertmans and Gy\u00f6rgy Konr\u00e1d''', Ludion 2013<br>\n''Closed Doors'', '''Eric Rinckhout''', Roberto Polo Gallery, 2012<br>\n''Closing Time'', '''Maarten Doorman en Eric Rinckhout''', Ludion | De Bezige Bij, 2010<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, Parcours 1966-2008'', '''Marc Ruyters''', Snoeck, 2008<br>\n''Een Winterreise'', '''Cees Nooteboom & Jan Vanriet''', Literarte, 2007<br>\n''De Testamenten'', Jan Vanriet, with text by '''Marc Ruyters and Luc Devisscher''', Davidsfonds Uitgeverij, 2005<br>\n''Transport'', '''Cees Nooteboom and Vera Scheef''', Lippisches Landesmuseum Detmold, 2004<br>\n''Transport'', '''Bernard Dewulf''', Art Concern, 2002<br>\n''De reiziger is blind'', '''Jean Pierre Rondas''', De Geus, 2001<br>\n''Caf\u00e9 Aurora'', '''Stefan Hertmans''', De Geus, 2000<br>\n''Jan Vanriet'', '''Freddy de Vree''', Lannoo, 1996<br>\n''Mati\u00e8re et M\u00e9moire'', '''Pierre Restany''', Centrum Elzenveld, 1993<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, or the Subtle Disruption'', '''Wim Meeuwis''', Internationale Culturele Samenwerking, Biennale di Venezia, 1984<br>\n''Jan Vanriet, L\u2019\u00e9tat de si\u00e8ge du regard'', '''Pierre Restany''', Galerie Isy Brachot, Paris, 1983<br>\n''Jan Vanriet'', '''Edward Lucie-Smith''', Uitgeverij Manteau, Antwerpen, & van Gennep, 1982\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.janvanriet.com/ Jan Vanriet - Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160109200851/http://simonelenaerts.be/ Simone Lenaerts - Official website]\n* [http://www.hollandsdiep.nl/ Hollands Diep]\n* [http://www.mennovanriet.be/ Menno Vanriet - Official website]\n* [http://www.caviarcontent.com/losangeles/directors/bram-vanriet/ Bram Vanriet - Caviar Content]\n* [http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/jan-vanriet-the-music-boy/ Jan Vanriet 'The Music Boy' at The New Art Gallery Walsall]\n* [https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?searchText=vanriet/ Jan Vanriet at The British Museum]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vanriet, Jan}}\n[[Category:Flemish painters]]\n[[Category:Flemish poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Vanriet"}
{"title_page": "Geert van Istendael", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Geert van Istendael\n| image       = Geert van Istendael.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =Writer, poet and essayist Geert van Istendael in 2017.\n| birth_name  = Geert Maria Mauritius Julianus Vanistendael\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1947|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Uccle]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgium\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = writer\n| known_for   =\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Geert van Istendael''' (born 29 March 1947) is the [[pseudonym]] of ''Geert Maria Mauritius Julianus Vanistendael'', a [[Belgium|Belgian]] writer, poet and essayist. He studied [[sociology]] and [[philosophy]] at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]. From 1987 until 1993, he worked as a journalist for the Belgian National Television and since 1993 he became a full-time writer. He is a brother of [[Frans Vanistendael]]. He is a supporter of [[Orangism (Belgium)|Orangism]].<ref>http://achillevandenbranden.blogspot.be/2010/03/mijn-nederland-geert-van-istendael.html</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*1983 ''De iguanodons van Bernissart''. (poems)\n*1987 ''Plattegronden''. Amsterdam (poems).\n*1989 ''Het Belgisch labyrint, of De schoonheid der wanstaltigheid''. (essays)\n*1991 ''Verhalen van het heggeland''. (stories)\n*1992 ''Arm Brussel''. Amsterdam (essays)\n*1994 ''Bekentenissen van een reactionair''. (essays)\n*1995 ''Vlaamse sprookjes''. (fairytales)\n*1996 ''Het geduld van de dingen''. (poems)\n*1997 ''Altrapsodie''. (novel)\n*1997 ''Anders is niet beter''. (essays)\n*1999 ''Nieuwe uitbarstingen''. (essays)\n*2001 ''Alle uitbarstingen''. (columns)\n*2003 ''De zwarte steen''. (novel)\n*2005 ''Mijn Nederland''. (essays)\n*2006 ''Alfabet van de globalisering''. (essays)\n*2007: ''Mijn Duitsland'' (essays)\n*2008: ''Kerstverhaal'' (with {{Interlanguage link multi|Judith Vanistendael|nl}})\n*2009: ''Gesprekken met mijn dode god''\n*2010: ''Tot het Nederlandse volk''\n*2012: ''Een geschiedenis van Belgi\u00eb''\n\n==Awards==\n* 1995 \u2013 {{Interlanguage link multi|Geuzenprijs|nl}} with [[Paul de Leeuw]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Flemish literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=iste001 Geert van Istendael]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022125148/http://devrijegedachte.nl/dvgtelevisie/dichters/afl-3/bibliografie.htm devrijegedachte.nl]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Istendael, Geert}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:Belgian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Flemish journalists]]\n[[Category:Belgian essayists]]\n[[Category:KU Leuven alumni]]\n[[Category:Belgian translators]]\n[[Category:German\u2013Dutch translators]]\n[[Category:Flemish poets]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Geert van Istendael\n| image       = Geert van Istendael.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =Writer, poet and essayist Geert van Istendael in 2017.\n| birth_name  = Geert Maria Mauritius Julianus Vanistendael\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1947|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Uccle]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgium\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = writer\n| known_for   =\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Geert van Istendael''' (born 29 March 1947) is the [[pseudonym]] of ''Geert Maria Mauritius Julianus Vanistendael'', a [[Belgium|Belgian]] writer, poet and essayist. He studied [[sociology]] and [[philosophy]] at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]. From 1987 until 1993, he worked as a journalist for the Belgian National Television and since 1993 he became a full-time writer. He is a brother of [[Frans Vanistendael]]. He is a supporter of [[Orangism (Belgium)|Orangism]].<ref>http://achillevandenbranden.blogspot.be/2010/03/mijn-nederland-geert-van-istendael.html</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*1983 ''De iguanodons van Bernissart''. (poems)\n*1987 ''Plattegronden''. Amsterdam (poems).\n*1989 ''Het Belgisch labyrint, of De schoonheid der wanstaltigheid''. (essays)\n*1991 ''Verhalen van het heggeland''. (stories)\n*1992 ''Arm Brussel''. Amsterdam (essays)\n*1994 ''Bekentenissen van een reactionair''. (essays)\n*1995 ''Vlaamse sprookjes''. (fairytales)\n*1996 ''Het geduld van de dingen''. (poems)\n*1997 ''Altrapsodie''. (novel)\n*1997 ''Anders is niet beter''. (essays)\n*1999 ''Nieuwe uitbarstingen''. (essays)\n*2001 ''Alle uitbarstingen''. (columns)\n*2003 ''De zwarte steen''. (novel)\n*2005 ''Mijn Nederland''. (essays)\n*2006 ''Alfabet van de globalisering''. (essays)\n*2007: ''Mijn Duitsland'' (essays)\n*2008: ''Kerstverhaal'' (with {{Interlanguage link multi|Judith Vanistendael|nl}})\n*2009: ''Gesprekken met mijn dode god''\n*2010: ''Tot het Nederlandse volk''\n*2012: ''Een geschiedenis van Belgi\u00eb''\n\n==Awards==\n* 1995 \u2013 {{Interlanguage link multi|Geuzenprijs|nl}} with [[Paul de Leeuw]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Flemish literature]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=iste001 Geert van Istendael]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022125148/http://devrijegedachte.nl/dvgtelevisie/dichters/afl-3/bibliografie.htm devrijegedachte.nl]\