{"title_page": "Jean-Philippe Toussaint", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer <!--for more information, see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]]-->\n| name        = Jean-Philippe Toussaint\n| image       = Jean-Philippe Toussaint, Florence (Italie), 2013.JPG\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Jean-Philippe Toussaint in 2013\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1957|11|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgian\n| alma_mater = [[Sciences Po]] (1978)\n| other_names =\n| occupation = {{hlist |Novelist |Screenwriter | Director}}\n| notableworks = {{ublist|''La Salle de bain''|''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision''|\u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb}}\n| awards = {{ublist|class=nowrap |[[Prix Victor-Rossel]]|[[Prix M\u00e9dicis]]|[[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]|[[Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award]]}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.jptoussaint.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jean-Philippe Toussaint''' (29 November 1957, [[Brussels]]) is a [[Belgian]] novelist, photographer and filmmaker. His books have been translated into more than twenty languages and he has had his photographs displayed in Brussels and Japan. Toussaint won the [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]] in 2005 for his novel ''Fuir'' (''Running Away''), second volume of the \u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb, a four-tome chronicle published over ten years and displaying the separation of Marie and her lover.<ref name=Garcin>{{cite web|last1=Garcin|first1=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|authorlink = J\u00e9r\u00f4me Garcin|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint : \"Je suis tr\u00e8s connu, mais personne ne le sait...\"|url=http://bibliobs.nouvelobs.com/rentree-litteraire-2013/20130829.OBS4927/jean-philippe-toussaint-je-suis-tres-connu-mais-personne-ne-le-sait.html|website=[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]|accessdate=30 August 2013|language=French}}</ref> His 2009 novel ''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' (''The Truth about Marie''), third volume of the cycle, won the [[Prix D\u00e9cembre]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Family===\nJean-Philippe Toussaint was born in Brussels, son of the Belgian journalist and writer Yvon Toussaint (1933\u20132013) and a bookseller mother of Lithuanian descent Monique Toussaint (n\u00e9e Lanskoronskis),<ref name=Soir2010>{{cite journal|last1=Crousse|first1=Nicolas|title=Les Toussaint, itin\u00e9raire d'une famille g\u00e2t\u00e9e|journal=[[Le Soir]]|date=13 November 2010|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/les-toussaint-itineraire-d-8217-une-famille-gatee_t-20101113-014M75.html|language=French}}</ref> but mostly raised in [[Paris]] where his father was the correspondent in France of the Belgian newspaper ''[[Le Soir]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Duplat|first1=Guy|title=Yvon Toussaint, mort d'un grand journaliste|journal=[[Le Soir]]|date=7 December 2013|url=http://www.lalibre.be/culture/medias-tele/yvon-toussaint-mort-d-un-grand-journaliste-52a2a7fd357004c37c87b32f|language=French}}</ref> He's the brother of the Belgian cinema producer Anne-Dominique Toussaint.\n\nHe lives in Brussels and [[Corsica]],<ref name=Garcin/> where his wife, Madeleine Santandrea (and mother of their two children) is from [[Bastia]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Le Bastiais Jean-Philippe Toussaint en lice pour le prix Goncourt 2009|journal=[[Corse-Matin]]|date=2 November 2009|url=http://www.corsematin.com/article/corse/bastia-le-bastiais-jean-philippe-toussaint-en-lice-pour-le-prix-goncourt-2009.16705.html|language=French}}</ref>\n\n===Early life and education===\nRaised in flourishing cultural milieu in Brussels, then after 1970 in Paris where he attended high school, he graduated from the [[Institut d'\u00e9tudes politiques de Paris]] (1979) and holds a master of Arts in contemporary history from the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] (1980).<ref name=Soir2010/><ref name=BioJPT>{{cite web|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint's Biography|url=http://www.jptoussaint.com/jean-philippe-toussaint.html|website=jptoussaint.com|accessdate=10 April 2015|language=French}}</ref> After his studies, he was engaged in teaching French for two years in [[M\u00e9d\u00e9a]], [[Algeria]] as an alternative to conscription;<ref name=Soir2010/><ref name=BioJPT/> he henceforth decided to devote himself to literature, considering cinema to be technically and financially too demanding.\n\n==Literary career==\nJean-Philippe Toussaint's first two plays ''Rideau'' (1981) and ''Les Draps de lit'' (1982) and his short novel ''\u00c9checs'' (1983) have never been published. He is strongly influenced by [[Samuel Beckett]]'s style<ref name=Guardian2011/> and generally by the [[Nouveau Roman]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacques|first1=Juliet|title=Rethinking the detective novel: Jean-Philippe Toussaint's Reticence|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/culture/2012/07/rethinking-detective-novel-jean-philippe-toussaints-reticence|website=NewStateman|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> He wrote his first novel, ''La Salle de bain'' (''The Bathroom'') in 1985 and submitted it to [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Lindon]], the influential publisher of [[Les \u00c9ditions de Minuit]] in Paris, who accepted it and became his exclusive publisher. The novel and its style were critically acclaimed and established Jean-Philippe Toussaint as a young and promising author. Subsequently, he published ''Monsieur'' (a novel that was earned a large following in Japan and Asia) and ''L'Appareil-photo'' in the late 1980s which confirmed his status as a writer<ref name=McCarthy2008>{{cite journal|last1=McCarthy|first1=Tom|title=Tryst and Shoot|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 December 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/14/books/review/McCarthy-t.html}}</ref> and allowed him to start a parallel career as a filmmaker. He directed two movies soon after: ''[[Monsieur (1990 film)|Monsieur]]'' (1990)\u2014distinguished by the [[Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award]]\u2014and ''La S\u00e9villane'' (1992).\n\nDuring a writing residency in [[Berlin]]<ref name=BioJPT/> in 1997 he wrote his most ironic and \"subtly comic\" novel ''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision''<ref name=Byrd2009>{{cite journal|last1=Byrd|first1=Christopher|title=Shanghai Express|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 December 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/books/review/Byrd-t.html}}</ref> which won the [[Prix Victor-Rossel]] in Belgium. After publishing an essay, ''Autoportrait (\u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger)'', based on his experiences living abroad, he then decided to embark on a series of novels (entitled \u00ab cycle of Marie Madeleine Marguerite de Montale \u00bb but formally known as \u00ab cycle of Marie \u00bb, named after Marie, the main protagonist) depicting the long and uncertain breakup of two lovers\u2014Marie and the narrator\u2014over four seasons during the course of a year. The books were written between 2000 and 2013 and constitute his ''[[Masterpiece|Magnum opus]]''.<ref name=Garcin/><ref name=Guardian2011>{{cite journal|last1=Lezard|first1=Nicholas|title=The Truth About Marie by Jean-Philippe Toussaint \u2013 review|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 September 2011|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/sep/06/truth-marie-jean-philippe-toussaint-review}}</ref> The \u00ab cycle of Marie \u00bb started in 2002 with ''Faire l'amour'' (''Making Love'', 2004), followed by ''Fuir'' in 2005 (''Running Away'', 2009)<ref name=Byrd2009/>\u2014awarded by the [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]] in France\u2014, ''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' in 2009 (''The Truth about Marie'', 2011)<ref name=Guardian2011/>\u2014[[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]\u2014and finally ''Nue'' in 2013 which closes the tetralogy.\n\nHis 2006 book ''La M\u00e9lancolie de Zidane''<ref>[http://www.lwbooks.co.uk/journals/newformations/archive/newformations62.html English translation of ''La m\u00e9lancolie de Zidane'']</ref> (2006) is a lyrical essay on the French football player [[Zinedine Zidane]]'s headbutting of the Italian player [[Marco Materazzi]] during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|2006 World Cup final]] in Berlin. Toussaint lived in Berlin at the time and was at the game. An English translation was published in 2007 in the British journal ''New Formations''.\n\nAlong with [[Jean Echenoz]], [[Laurent Mauvignier]], [[Marie NDiaye]] or [[\u00c9ric Chevillard]], Jean-Philippe Toussaint is associated with the so-called \u00ab Style [des \u00e9ditions de] Minuit \u00bb.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bertrand|first1=Michel|last2=Germoni|first2=Karine|last3=Jauer|first3=Annick|title=Existe-t-il un style Minuit ?|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Provence|Universit\u00e9 de Provence]]|isbn=978-2853999397|page=274|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Voisset-Veysseyre|first1=C\u00e9cile|title=Peut-on parler d'un style Minuit?|url=http://www.slate.fr/story/96455/style-minuit|website=Slate.fr|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n*''La Salle de bain'' (Paris, [[Les \u00c9ditions de Minuit|Minuit]], 1985)\n**''The Bathroom'' (Champaign, [[Dalkey Archive Press]], 2008), translated by Nancy Amphoux and Paul De Angelis.\n*''Monsieur'' (Minuit, 1986)<ref name=Danto1991/>\n**''Monsieur'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2008),<ref name=Danto1991>{{cite journal|last1=Danto|first1=Ginger|title=No Zeal, Please|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 October 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/06/books/no-zeal-please.html}}</ref> translated by John Lambert.\n*''L'Appareil-photo'' (Minuit, 1989)<ref name=McCarthy2008/>\n**''Camera'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2008),<ref name=McCarthy2008/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''La R\u00e9ticence'' (Minuit, 1991)\n**''Reticence'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2012), translated by John Lambert.\n*''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision'' (Minuit, 1997);<ref name=Press2005/> [[Prix Victor-Rossel]]\n**''Television'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2007),<ref name=Press2005>{{cite journal|last1=Press|first1=Joy|title='Television': Le Boob Tube|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 January 2005|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/02/books/review/02PRESS.html}}</ref> translated by Jordan Stump.\n*''Autoportrait (\u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger)'' (Minuit, 2000)\n**''Self-Portrait Abroad'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2010), translated by John Lambert.\n*''La M\u00e9lancolie de Zidane'' (Minuit, 2006), essay\n**\"Zidane's Melancholy\" within ''Best European Fiction'' (Champaign, Dalky Archive Press, 2009), translated by Thangam Ravindranathan and Timothy Bewes\n*''L'Urgence et la Patience'' (Minuit, 2012), essay\n**''Urgency and Patience'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2013), translated by Edward Gauvin\n*''[https://fitzcarraldo-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/c2e128388771777395ce7c67cf21a14e.pdf Football'' (Fitzcarraldo Editions, 2016), translated by Shaun Whiteside.]\n\n'''\u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb'''\n*''Faire l'amour'' (Minuit, 2002)\n**''Making Love'' (New York, [[The New Press]], 2004), translated by [[Linda Coverdale]]\n*''Fuir'' (Minuit, 2005);<ref name=Byrd2009/> [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]]\n**''Running Away'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2009),<ref name=Byrd2009/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' (Minuit, 2009);<ref name=Guardian2011/> [[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]\n**''The Truth about Marie'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2011),<ref name=Guardian2011/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''Nue'' (Minuit, 2013)\n**''Naked'' (Dalkey Archive Press, 2016), translated by Edward Gauvin.\n\n==Films==\n*''La Salle de bain'' (1989) by [[John Lvoff]], Screenwriter. Starring [[Tom Novembre]], [[Gunilla Karlzen]].\n*''[[Monsieur (1990 film)|Monsieur]]'' (1990), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Dominic Gould]], [[Wojciech Pszoniak]].\n*''La S\u00e9villane'' (1992), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Mireille Perrier]], Jean-Claude Adelin, [[Jean Yanne]].\n*''La Patinoire'' (1999), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Tom Novembre]], [[Mireille Perrier]], [[Dolor\u00e8s Chaplin]], [[Bruce Campbell]], [[Marie-France Pisier]], [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]].\n*''Trois fragments de \"Fuir\" : Louvre/Chine/Elbe'' (short-films, 2011), Director. Starring [[Dolor\u00e8s Chaplin]].\n\n==Exhibitions==\nAs a photographer, he held his first major exhibition in 2001 in [[Osaka]], Japan then later obtained a residency in 2006 in [[Toulouse]], France where he extended his work to installations mixing neons, films, photos and books as supports. This work became also the basis of a more ambitious exhibition which took place in 2009 in [[Guangzhou|Canton, China]]. In 2012, as invited-artist Toussaint curated an important exhibition entitled \"Livre/Louvre\" at the [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]] in Paris. In addition to photographs, original short-films (entitled ''Trois fragments de \"Fuir\"'') and various installations, the show featured an excerpt from the original manuscript of ''[[En attendant Godot]]'' by [[Samuel Beckett]] and a copy of the eighth edition of [[Dante]]'s ''[[Divina Commedia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toussaint|first1=Jean-Philippe|title=Livre/Louvre|url=http://www.jptoussaint.com/livre-louvre.html}}</ref>\n\n==Distinction==\n*Elected member (seat #9) of the [[Acad\u00e9mie royale de langue et de litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aises de Belgique]] (2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint|url=http://www.arllfb.be/composition/membres/toussaint.html|website=ARLLFB|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.jptoussaint.com/ Jean-Philippe Toussaint's personal web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721194908/http://auteurs.contemporain.info/jean-philippe-toussaint/ Critical bibliography (Auteurs.contemporain.info)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080705083440/http://www.dalkeyarchive.com/article/show/253 Essay by Warren Motte on 'Reading Jean-Philippe Toussaint]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award 1981\u20132000}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toussaint, Jean-Phillipe}}\n[[Category:Belgian writers in French]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of Lithuanian descent]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Prix M\u00e9dicis winners]]\n[[Category:Prix D\u00e9cembre winners]]\n[[Category:People from Brussels]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie royale de langue et de litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aises de Belgique]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer <!--for more information, see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]]-->\n| name        = Jean-Philippe Toussaint\n| image       = Jean-Philippe Toussaint, Florence (Italie), 2013.JPG\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Jean-Philippe Toussaint in 2013\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1957|11|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Brussels]], Belgium\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Belgian\n| alma_mater = [[Sciences Po]] (1978)\n| other_names =\n| occupation = {{hlist |Novelist |Screenwriter | Director}}\n| notableworks = {{ublist|''La Salle de bain''|''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision''|\u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb}}\n| awards = {{ublist|class=nowrap |[[Prix Victor-Rossel]]|[[Prix M\u00e9dicis]]|[[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]|[[Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award]]}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.jptoussaint.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jean-Philippe Toussaint''' (29 November 1957, [[Brussels]]) is a [[Belgian]] novelist, photographer and filmmaker. His books have been translated into more than twenty languages and he has had his photographs displayed in Brussels and Japan. Toussaint won the [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]] in 2005 for his novel ''Fuir'' (''Running Away''), second volume of the \u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb, a four-tome chronicle published over ten years and displaying the separation of Marie and her lover.<ref name=Garcin>{{cite web|last1=Garcin|first1=J\u00e9r\u00f4me|authorlink = J\u00e9r\u00f4me Garcin|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint : \"Je suis tr\u00e8s connu, mais personne ne le sait...\"|url=http://bibliobs.nouvelobs.com/rentree-litteraire-2013/20130829.OBS4927/jean-philippe-toussaint-je-suis-tres-connu-mais-personne-ne-le-sait.html|website=[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]|accessdate=30 August 2013|language=French}}</ref> His 2009 novel ''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' (''The Truth about Marie''), third volume of the cycle, won the [[Prix D\u00e9cembre]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Family===\nJean-Philippe Toussaint was born in Brussels, son of the Belgian journalist and writer Yvon Toussaint (1933\u20132013) and a bookseller mother of Lithuanian descent Monique Toussaint (n\u00e9e Lanskoronskis),<ref name=Soir2010>{{cite journal|last1=Crousse|first1=Nicolas|title=Les Toussaint, itin\u00e9raire d'une famille g\u00e2t\u00e9e|journal=[[Le Soir]]|date=13 November 2010|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/les-toussaint-itineraire-d-8217-une-famille-gatee_t-20101113-014M75.html|language=French}}</ref> but mostly raised in [[Paris]] where his father was the correspondent in France of the Belgian newspaper ''[[Le Soir]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Duplat|first1=Guy|title=Yvon Toussaint, mort d'un grand journaliste|journal=[[Le Soir]]|date=7 December 2013|url=http://www.lalibre.be/culture/medias-tele/yvon-toussaint-mort-d-un-grand-journaliste-52a2a7fd357004c37c87b32f|language=French}}</ref> He's the brother of the Belgian cinema producer Anne-Dominique Toussaint.\n\nHe lives in Brussels and [[Corsica]],<ref name=Garcin/> where his wife, Madeleine Santandrea (and mother of their two children) is from [[Bastia]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Le Bastiais Jean-Philippe Toussaint en lice pour le prix Goncourt 2009|journal=[[Corse-Matin]]|date=2 November 2009|url=http://www.corsematin.com/article/corse/bastia-le-bastiais-jean-philippe-toussaint-en-lice-pour-le-prix-goncourt-2009.16705.html|language=French}}</ref>\n\n===Early life and education===\nRaised in flourishing cultural milieu in Brussels, then after 1970 in Paris where he attended high school, he graduated from the [[Institut d'\u00e9tudes politiques de Paris]] (1979) and holds a master of Arts in contemporary history from the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] (1980).<ref name=Soir2010/><ref name=BioJPT>{{cite web|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint's Biography|url=http://www.jptoussaint.com/jean-philippe-toussaint.html|website=jptoussaint.com|accessdate=10 April 2015|language=French}}</ref> After his studies, he was engaged in teaching French for two years in [[M\u00e9d\u00e9a]], [[Algeria]] as an alternative to conscription;<ref name=Soir2010/><ref name=BioJPT/> he henceforth decided to devote himself to literature, considering cinema to be technically and financially too demanding.\n\n==Literary career==\nJean-Philippe Toussaint's first two plays ''Rideau'' (1981) and ''Les Draps de lit'' (1982) and his short novel ''\u00c9checs'' (1983) have never been published. He is strongly influenced by [[Samuel Beckett]]'s style<ref name=Guardian2011/> and generally by the [[Nouveau Roman]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacques|first1=Juliet|title=Rethinking the detective novel: Jean-Philippe Toussaint's Reticence|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/culture/2012/07/rethinking-detective-novel-jean-philippe-toussaints-reticence|website=NewStateman|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> He wrote his first novel, ''La Salle de bain'' (''The Bathroom'') in 1985 and submitted it to [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Lindon]], the influential publisher of [[Les \u00c9ditions de Minuit]] in Paris, who accepted it and became his exclusive publisher. The novel and its style were critically acclaimed and established Jean-Philippe Toussaint as a young and promising author. Subsequently, he published ''Monsieur'' (a novel that was earned a large following in Japan and Asia) and ''L'Appareil-photo'' in the late 1980s which confirmed his status as a writer<ref name=McCarthy2008>{{cite journal|last1=McCarthy|first1=Tom|title=Tryst and Shoot|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=12 December 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/14/books/review/McCarthy-t.html}}</ref> and allowed him to start a parallel career as a filmmaker. He directed two movies soon after: ''[[Monsieur (1990 film)|Monsieur]]'' (1990)\u2014distinguished by the [[Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award]]\u2014and ''La S\u00e9villane'' (1992).\n\nDuring a writing residency in [[Berlin]]<ref name=BioJPT/> in 1997 he wrote his most ironic and \"subtly comic\" novel ''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision''<ref name=Byrd2009>{{cite journal|last1=Byrd|first1=Christopher|title=Shanghai Express|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 December 2009|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/27/books/review/Byrd-t.html}}</ref> which won the [[Prix Victor-Rossel]] in Belgium. After publishing an essay, ''Autoportrait (\u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger)'', based on his experiences living abroad, he then decided to embark on a series of novels (entitled \u00ab cycle of Marie Madeleine Marguerite de Montale \u00bb but formally known as \u00ab cycle of Marie \u00bb, named after Marie, the main protagonist) depicting the long and uncertain breakup of two lovers\u2014Marie and the narrator\u2014over four seasons during the course of a year. The books were written between 2000 and 2013 and constitute his ''[[Masterpiece|Magnum opus]]''.<ref name=Garcin/><ref name=Guardian2011>{{cite journal|last1=Lezard|first1=Nicholas|title=The Truth About Marie by Jean-Philippe Toussaint \u2013 review|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 September 2011|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/sep/06/truth-marie-jean-philippe-toussaint-review}}</ref> The \u00ab cycle of Marie \u00bb started in 2002 with ''Faire l'amour'' (''Making Love'', 2004), followed by ''Fuir'' in 2005 (''Running Away'', 2009)<ref name=Byrd2009/>\u2014awarded by the [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]] in France\u2014, ''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' in 2009 (''The Truth about Marie'', 2011)<ref name=Guardian2011/>\u2014[[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]\u2014and finally ''Nue'' in 2013 which closes the tetralogy.\n\nHis 2006 book ''La M\u00e9lancolie de Zidane''<ref>[http://www.lwbooks.co.uk/journals/newformations/archive/newformations62.html English translation of ''La m\u00e9lancolie de Zidane'']</ref> (2006) is a lyrical essay on the French football player [[Zinedine Zidane]]'s headbutting of the Italian player [[Marco Materazzi]] during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|2006 World Cup final]] in Berlin. Toussaint lived in Berlin at the time and was at the game. An English translation was published in 2007 in the British journal ''New Formations''.\n\nAlong with [[Jean Echenoz]], [[Laurent Mauvignier]], [[Marie NDiaye]] or [[\u00c9ric Chevillard]], Jean-Philippe Toussaint is associated with the so-called \u00ab Style [des \u00e9ditions de] Minuit \u00bb.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bertrand|first1=Michel|last2=Germoni|first2=Karine|last3=Jauer|first3=Annick|title=Existe-t-il un style Minuit ?|date=2014|publisher=[[University of Provence|Universit\u00e9 de Provence]]|isbn=978-2853999397|page=274|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Voisset-Veysseyre|first1=C\u00e9cile|title=Peut-on parler d'un style Minuit?|url=http://www.slate.fr/story/96455/style-minuit|website=Slate.fr|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\n*''La Salle de bain'' (Paris, [[Les \u00c9ditions de Minuit|Minuit]], 1985)\n**''The Bathroom'' (Champaign, [[Dalkey Archive Press]], 2008), translated by Nancy Amphoux and Paul De Angelis.\n*''Monsieur'' (Minuit, 1986)<ref name=Danto1991/>\n**''Monsieur'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2008),<ref name=Danto1991>{{cite journal|last1=Danto|first1=Ginger|title=No Zeal, Please|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 October 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/06/books/no-zeal-please.html}}</ref> translated by John Lambert.\n*''L'Appareil-photo'' (Minuit, 1989)<ref name=McCarthy2008/>\n**''Camera'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2008),<ref name=McCarthy2008/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''La R\u00e9ticence'' (Minuit, 1991)\n**''Reticence'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2012), translated by John Lambert.\n*''La T\u00e9l\u00e9vision'' (Minuit, 1997);<ref name=Press2005/> [[Prix Victor-Rossel]]\n**''Television'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2007),<ref name=Press2005>{{cite journal|last1=Press|first1=Joy|title='Television': Le Boob Tube|journal=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 January 2005|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/02/books/review/02PRESS.html}}</ref> translated by Jordan Stump.\n*''Autoportrait (\u00e0 l'\u00e9tranger)'' (Minuit, 2000)\n**''Self-Portrait Abroad'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2010), translated by John Lambert.\n*''La M\u00e9lancolie de Zidane'' (Minuit, 2006), essay\n**\"Zidane's Melancholy\" within ''Best European Fiction'' (Champaign, Dalky Archive Press, 2009), translated by Thangam Ravindranathan and Timothy Bewes\n*''L'Urgence et la Patience'' (Minuit, 2012), essay\n**''Urgency and Patience'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2013), translated by Edward Gauvin\n*''[https://fitzcarraldo-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/c2e128388771777395ce7c67cf21a14e.pdf Football'' (Fitzcarraldo Editions, 2016), translated by Shaun Whiteside.]\n\n'''\u00ab Cycle of Marie \u00bb'''\n*''Faire l'amour'' (Minuit, 2002)\n**''Making Love'' (New York, [[The New Press]], 2004), translated by [[Linda Coverdale]]\n*''Fuir'' (Minuit, 2005);<ref name=Byrd2009/> [[Prix M\u00e9dicis]]\n**''Running Away'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2009),<ref name=Byrd2009/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur Marie'' (Minuit, 2009);<ref name=Guardian2011/> [[Prix D\u00e9cembre]]\n**''The Truth about Marie'' (Champaign, Dalkey Archive Press, 2011),<ref name=Guardian2011/> translated by Matthew B. Smith.\n*''Nue'' (Minuit, 2013)\n**''Naked'' (Dalkey Archive Press, 2016), translated by Edward Gauvin.\n\n==Films==\n*''La Salle de bain'' (1989) by [[John Lvoff]], Screenwriter. Starring [[Tom Novembre]], [[Gunilla Karlzen]].\n*''[[Monsieur (1990 film)|Monsieur]]'' (1990), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Dominic Gould]], [[Wojciech Pszoniak]].\n*''La S\u00e9villane'' (1992), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Mireille Perrier]], Jean-Claude Adelin, [[Jean Yanne]].\n*''La Patinoire'' (1999), Director / Screenwriter. Starring [[Tom Novembre]], [[Mireille Perrier]], [[Dolor\u00e8s Chaplin]], [[Bruce Campbell]], [[Marie-France Pisier]], [[Jean-Pierre Cassel]].\n*''Trois fragments de \"Fuir\" : Louvre/Chine/Elbe'' (short-films, 2011), Director. Starring [[Dolor\u00e8s Chaplin]].\n\n==Exhibitions==\nAs a photographer, he held his first major exhibition in 2001 in [[Osaka]], Japan then later obtained a residency in 2006 in [[Toulouse]], France where he extended his work to installations mixing neons, films, photos and books as supports. This work became also the basis of a more ambitious exhibition which took place in 2009 in [[Guangzhou|Canton, China]]. In 2012, as invited-artist Toussaint curated an important exhibition entitled \"Livre/Louvre\" at the [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]] in Paris. In addition to photographs, original short-films (entitled ''Trois fragments de \"Fuir\"'') and various installations, the show featured an excerpt from the original manuscript of ''[[En attendant Godot]]'' by [[Samuel Beckett]] and a copy of the eighth edition of [[Dante]]'s ''[[Divina Commedia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toussaint|first1=Jean-Philippe|title=Livre/Louvre|url=http://www.jptoussaint.com/livre-louvre.html}}</ref>\n\n==Distinction==\n*Elected member (seat #9) of the [[Acad\u00e9mie royale de langue et de litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aises de Belgique]] (2014)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Philippe Toussaint|url=http://www.arllfb.be/composition/membres/toussaint.html|website=ARLLFB|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.jptoussaint.com/ Jean-Philippe Toussaint's personal web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721194908/http://auteurs.contemporain.info/jean-philippe-toussaint/ Critical bibliography (Auteurs.contemporain.info)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080705083440/http://www.dalkeyarchive.com/article/show/253 Essay by Warren Motte on 'Reading Jean-Philippe Toussaint]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Andr\u00e9 Cavens Award 1981\u20132000}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toussaint, Jean-Phillipe}}\n[[Category:Belgian writers in French]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of Lithuanian descent]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Prix M\u00e9dicis winners]]\n[[Category:Prix D\u00e9cembre winners]]\n[[Category:People from Brussels]]\n[[Category:Members of the Acad\u00e9mie royale de langue et de litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aises de Belgique]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Philippe_Toussaint"}
{"title_page": "Philippe Roberts-Jones", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Philippe Roberts-Jones\n| image         = Philippe Roberts-Jones portrait 196712 - cropped.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Portrait of Philippe Roberts-Jones in 1967\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1924|11|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ixelles]], Belgium\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|8|9|1924|11|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = Uccle, Belgium <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academieroyale.be/cgi?lg=fr&pag=774&tab=87&rec=2305&frm=0|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s du baron Roberts-Jones, professeur \u00e9m\u00e9rite de l'ULB, conservateur en chef honoraire des Mus\u00e9es royaux des Beaux-Arts de Belgique et secr\u00e9taire perp\u00e9tuel honoraire de l'Acad\u00e9mie|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie Royal de Belgique|language=fr}}</ref>\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\nBaron '''Philippe Roberts-Jones''' (8 November 1924 \u2013 9 August 2016) was a Belgian [[art historian]] who was the head of conservation of the [[Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium]]. A member of the [[Royal Academy of Science, Letters and Fine Arts of Belgium]], of which he was president in 1980, he was also a member of the [[Free Academy of Belgium]] and professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]]. He was also a published [[poet]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Ixelles]], Belgium, on 8 November 1924, Philippe Roberts-Jones belongs to a family of three generations of lawyers, descending from a [[British people|British]] family established in [[Brussels]] at the beginning of the 19th century and that has been active in the [[coachwork]] industry.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Philippe Roberts-Jones |work= Dictionary of Art Historians|url = https://dictionaryofarthistorians.org/robertsjonesp.htm|editor-first= Lee |editor-last=Sorensen|accessdate = 2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nHis father [[Robert Roberts-Jones]] (1893\u20131943), a lawyer, was a member of the [[Belgian Resistance]] executed by the Germans at the ''[[Tir national]]'' on October 20, 1943.\n\nPhilippe Roberts-Jones died on 9 August 2016 at the age of 91.<ref>\"[http://www.lesoir.be/1287895/article/culture/arts-plastiques/2016-08-10/mort-philippe-roberts-jones Mort de Philippe Roberts-Jones]\", ''Le Soir'', 10.08.2016. Retrieved 2016-08-11.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.bruzz.be/nl/actua/kmskb-conservator-roberts-jones-overleden KMSKB-conservator Roberts-Jones overleden]\", ''BRUZZ.be'', 10.08.2016. Retrieved 2016-08-11.</ref>\n\n== Prizes ==\n*[[Prix \u00c9mile Polak]] from the [[Belgian Royal Academy of French Language and Literature]], 1957, for ''Amour et autres visages''\n*[[Prix Malherbe]] of the [[Province of Brabant]], 1976, for ''L'Art Majeur''\n*[[Prix du rayonnement de la langue fran\u00e7aise]], from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]], 1980, for his collected output\n*[[Grand prix de po\u00e9sie de l'Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]], 1985\n*[[Prix Louis-Guillaume]] for [[prose poetry]], 2002, for ''Domaines en cours''\n*[[Grand prix international Lucian Blaga]], 2006\n\n== Distinctions ==\nRobert-Jones was made a [[Baron]] by King [[Baudouin of Belgium|Baudouin]] in 1988.\n\n{{colbegin}}\n;Belgium \n*Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Order of the Crown]]\n*Grand Officer of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]]\n*Volunteers' Medal for War\n*Commemorative Medal of the 1940\u20131945 War, with sabres\n*Civic Medal, first class\n\n;France \n*Commandeur of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n*Commandeur of the [[ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n\n;Spain\n*Commander of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n\n; Italy \n*Commander of the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Italy]]\n\n; Finland \n*Grand Officer of the [[Order of the Lion of Finland]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Work ==\nAs a poet he publishes under the name '''Philippe Jones'''.  Among his published works are:\n*''Le Voyageur de la nuit''\n*''Amours et autres visages''\n*''\u00catre selon''\n*''Racine ouverte''\n*''Un espace renou\u00e9''\n\nAs an art historian, he is interested in the work  of [[Honor\u00e9 Daumier]] and in contemporary [[engraving]]; another field of interest is the work of Belgian painter [[Lismonde]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n*1973: ''L'Interm\u00e9diaire des g\u00e9n\u00e9alogistes'', \"De belgis illustribus. Les quartiers d'ascendance de Philippe Roberts-Jones\", n\u00b0 167, 1973, p.&nbsp;328-332. (by Denise Lelarge, Suzanne Roberts-Jones-Goemaere, [[Estelle van Win]], [[Marcel Berg\u00e9]], J. Fobe and L. Poplemont)\n*1981: Paul Legrain, ''Dictionnaire des Belges'', Bruxelles, 1981\n*2010: Karel Logist, \"En po\u00e9sie avec Dr Roberts et Mr Jones\", dans ''Le Carnet et les Instants'', n\u00b0 160, Brussels, February/March 2010, p.&nbsp;19-20\n\n{{Portal|poetry|Belgium}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.arllfb.be/composition/membres/jones.html Biography] at the site of the Belgian Royal Academy of French Language and Literature\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts-Jones, Philippe}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ixelles]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Barons of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Belgian art historians]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Crown (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Academy of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Free University of Brussels faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century historians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Lion of Finland]]\n[[Category:Belgian male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Belgian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Belgian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Philippe Roberts-Jones\n| image         = Philippe Roberts-Jones portrait 196712 - cropped.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Portrait of Philippe Roberts-Jones in 1967\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1924|11|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ixelles]], Belgium\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2016|8|9|1924|11|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = Uccle, Belgium <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academieroyale.be/cgi?lg=fr&pag=774&tab=87&rec=2305&frm=0|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s du baron Roberts-Jones, professeur \u00e9m\u00e9rite de l'ULB, conservateur en chef honoraire des Mus\u00e9es royaux des Beaux-Arts de Belgique et secr\u00e9taire perp\u00e9tuel honoraire de l'Acad\u00e9mie|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie Royal de Belgique|language=fr}}</ref>\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\nBaron '''Philippe Roberts-Jones''' (8 November 1924 \u2013 9 August 2016) was a Belgian [[art historian]] who was the head of conservation of the [[Royal Museums of Fine Arts of Belgium]]. A member of the [[Royal Academy of Science, Letters and Fine Arts of Belgium]], of which he was president in 1980, he was also a member of the [[Free Academy of Belgium]] and professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]]. He was also a published [[poet]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Ixelles]], Belgium, on 8 November 1924, Philippe Roberts-Jones belongs to a family of three generations of lawyers, descending from a [[British people|British]] family established in [[Brussels]] at the beginning of the 19th century and that has been active in the [[coachwork]] industry.<ref>{{Cite web|title